{{Same-sex unions}}
<!-- Don't add to the number of states without naming the state(s) or without citing evidence -->
[[Same-sex marriage]]s are recognized by the [[United States]] federal government and granted by 34 states;{{efn|These states are [[Same-sex marriage in Alaska|Alaska]], [[Same-sex marriage in Arizona|Arizona]], [[Same-sex marriage in California|California]], [[Same-sex marriage in Colorado|Colorado]], [[Same-sex marriage in Connecticut|Connecticut]], [[Same-sex marriage in Delaware|Delaware]], [[Same-sex marriage in Hawaii|Hawaii]], [[Same-sex marriage in Idaho|Idaho]], [[Same-sex marriage in Illinois|Illinois]], [[Same-sex marriage in Indiana|Indiana]], [[Same-sex marriage in Iowa|Iowa]], [[Same-sex marriage in Maine|Maine]], [[Same-sex marriage in Maryland|Maryland]], [[Same-sex marriage in Massachusetts|Massachusetts]], [[Same-sex marriage in Minnesota|Minnesota]], [[Same-sex marriage in Montana|Montana]], [[Same-sex marriage in Nevada|Nevada]], [[Same-sex marriage in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]], [[Same-sex marriage in New Jersey|New Jersey]], [[Same-sex marriage in New Mexico|New Mexico]], [[Same-sex marriage in New York|New York]], [[Same-sex marriage in North Carolina|North Carolina]], [[Same-sex marriage in Oklahoma|Oklahoma]], [[Same-sex marriage in Oregon|Oregon]], [[Same-sex marriage in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]], [[Same-sex marriage in Rhode Island|Rhode Island]], [[Same-sex marriage in South Carolina|South Carolina]],  [[Same-sex marriage in Utah|Utah]], [[Same-sex marriage in Vermont|Vermont]], [[Same-sex marriage in Virginia|Virginia]], [[Same-sex marriage in Washington state|Washington]], [[Same-sex marriage in West Virginia|West Virginia]], [[Same-sex marriage in Wisconsin|Wisconsin]], and [[Same-sex marriage in Wyoming|Wyoming]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Same-Sex Marriage Laws|url=http://www.ncsl.org/research/human-services/same-sex-marriage-laws.aspx |publisher=National Conference of State Legislatures |date=October 16, 2014| accessdate=January 1, 2014}}</ref>}} the [[Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia|District of Columbia]]; select local jurisdictions in [[Same-sex marriage in Kansas|Kansas]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Missouri|Missouri]]; and 11 [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions|Native American tribal jurisdictions]].{{efn|[[Cheyenne and Arapaho Tribes]], [[Confederated Tribes of the Colville Reservation]], [[Coquille Indian Tribe|Coquille]], [[Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians]], [[Mashantucket Pequot]], [[Pokagon Band of Potawatomi Indians]], [[Puyallup tribe|Puyallup]], [[Iipay Nation of Santa Ysabel|Santa Ysabel Tribe]], [[Leech Lake Band of Ojibwe]], [[Suquamish tribe|Suquamish]] and [[Wind River Indian Reservation]]}} In addition, [[Same-sex marriage in Missouri|Missouri]] recognizes same-sex marriages established in other jurisdictions. Several hundred marriage licenses were issued to same-sex couples in [[Same-sex marriage in Michigan|Michigan]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Arkansas|Arkansas]] between the time their bans were struck down by federal or state courts and when those rulings were [[Stay of proceedings#United States|stayed]]. Most Americans live in a jurisdiction where same-sex couples can legally marry.

The movement to obtain [[Rights and responsibilities of marriages in the United States|civil marriage rights]] and benefits for same-sex couples in the United States began in the 1970s,<ref>{{cite web|last=Gumbel|first=Andrew|title=The Great Undoing?|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/2009/06/20/great-undoing|work=[[The Advocate]]|accessdate=July 9, 2012}}</ref> but became increasingly prominent in U.S. politics following the 1993 [[Hawaii Supreme Court]] decision in ''[[Baehr v. Miike|Baehr v. Lewin]]'' that declared that state's prohibition to be unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web|title=Same Sex Marriage Laws – History|url=http://www.ncsl.org/issues-research/human-services/same-sex-marriage-laws.aspx|publisher=National Conference of State Legislatures|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref> During the 21st century, public support for same-sex marriage has grown considerably,<ref name="columbia.edu">{{cite journal|url=http://www.columbia.edu/~jrl2124/Lax_Phillips_Gay_Policy_Responsiveness_2009.pdf|title=Gay Rights in the States: Public Opinion and Policy Responsiveness|format=PDF|pages=67–86|doi=10.1017/S0003055409990050|date=August 2009|journal=American Political Science Review|volume=103|issue=3|accessdate=December 20, 2011|first=JEFFREY R.|last=LAX}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Silver|first=Nate|title=Support for Gay Marriage Outweighs Opposition in Polls|url=http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/09/support-for-gay-marriage-outweighs-opposition-in-polls/|accessdate=October 28, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 9, 2012}}</ref> and national polls conducted since 2011 show that a majority of Americans support legalizing it. On May 17, 2004, [[Same-sex marriage in Massachusetts|Massachusetts]] became the first U.S. state and the sixth jurisdiction in the world to legalize same-sex marriage following the [[Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court|Supreme Judicial Court]]'s decision in ''[[Goodridge v. Department of Public Health]]'' six months earlier.<ref name="festive">{{cite news|last=Belluck|first=Oam|title=With Festive Mood, Gay Weddings Begin in Massachusetts |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/17/national/17CND-GAYS.html |accessdate=January 11, 2014|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 17, 2004}}</ref>  On May 9, 2012, [[Barack Obama]] became the first sitting [[President of the United States|U.S. president]] to publicly declare support for the legalization of same-sex marriage.<ref name="obamasupport-ABCNews">{{cite news|last=Staff|first=ABC News|title=Obama Affirms Support for Same-Sex Marriage |url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/video/obama-sex-marriage-legal-16312904|accessdate=March 20, 2013|newspaper=ABC News|date=May 9, 2012}}</ref> On November 6, 2012, [[Maine Question 1, 2012|Maine]], [[Maryland Question 6|Maryland]], and [[Washington Referendum 74|Washington]] became the first states to legalize same-sex marriage through popular vote.

People seeking court-ordered recognition of their same-sex marriages based on their specific circumstances have had varying degrees of success. The Seventh Circuit and a U.S. district court have each required Indiana to recognize a marriage where one plaintiff is [[terminal illness|terminally ill]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson |first=Charles D. |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/court-orders-indiana-recognize-1-gay-marriage |title=Court orders Indiana to recognize 1 gay marriage |publisher=Bigstory.ap.org |date=July 1, 2014 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/09/12/indiana-recognizes-second-same-sex-marriage/15513075/ |publisher=USA Today |title=Indiana recognizes 2nd same-sex marriage |accessdate=September 12, 2014}}</ref> U.S. district courts in Arizona and Florida have each required a state to recognize a same-sex marriage for the purpose of issuing or amending a death certificate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2014/09/12/court-orders-arizona-to-recognize-one-same-sex-marriage/ |publisher=Washington Post |title=Court orders Arizona to recognize one same-sex marriage |accessdate=September 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stutzman|first1=Rene|title=Tallahassee federal judge throws out Florida's ban on same-sex marriage |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/os-gay-marriage-ban-florida-federal-judge-20140821-story.html |accessdate= October 9, 2014|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=August 21, 2014}}</ref> and a U.S. district court in Ohio issued a similar order with respect to four birth certificates before the case was reversed on appeal.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Metro Weekly|date=April 16, 2014 |accessdate=October 6, 2014|title=Federal judge grants partial stay in Ohio marriage-ban ruling| url=http://www.metroweekly.com/poliglot/2014/04/federal-judge-grants-partial-stay-in-ohio-marriage.html |first=Justin |last=Snow}}</ref> A Florida state court has recognized an out-of state same-sex marriage to allow a widower to serve as executor of his spouse's estate.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Duret |first1=Daphne |title=Palm Beach County judge declares gay marriage ban unconstitutional |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/news/local/palm-beach-county-judge-declares-gay-marriage-ban-/ngwM5/|accessdate=September 6, 2014|work=Palm Beach Post|date=August 5, 2014}}</ref> Similar plaintiffs have appealed adverse decisions or had rulings in their favor stayed pending appeal in several states.{{efn|In ''[[Tanco v. Haslam]]'', subsequently reversed on appeal to the Sixth Circuit, a U.S. district court ordered Tennessee to recognize the same-sex marriages of three plaintiff couples. In ''Czekala-Chatham v. Melancon'', a lesbian couple asks Mississippi to recognize their California marriage so they can divorce. There are two such divorce cases being litigated in Texas. In ''Hard v. Bentley'', a man asks Alabama to recognize him as a widower as part of a wrongful death suit.}}

Since the U.S. Supreme Court struck down the law barring federal recognition of same-sex marriage in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'' on June 26, 2013, U.S. district courts in 21 states{{efn|The rulings striking down same-sex marriage bans are from U.S. district courts serving (and affect) the following states: [[Same-sex marriage in Utah#Lawsuit|Utah]],<ref name="Watkins, Tom">{{cite news |last=Watkins |first=Tom|title=In Utah, judge's ruling ignites same-sex marriage frenzy |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/12/20/justice/utah-same-sex-marriage-ruling/| accessdate=December 23, 2013 |newspaper=CNN| date=December 20, 2013 }}</ref> [[Bishop v. United States|Oklahoma]],<ref name="chicagotribune1">{{cite news|last=Brandes|first=Heide|title=U.S. judge rules Oklahoma gay marriage ban unconstitutional |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/sns-rt-us-usa-gaymarriage-oklahoma-20140114,0,7810387.story |accessdate=January 15, 2014|agency=Reuters|work=Chicago Tribune|date=January 14, 2014 }}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Virginia#Bostic v. Schaefer|Virginia]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Simpson|first= Ian|title= Federal judge strikes down Virginia's ban on gay marriage |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/02/14/us-usa-gaymarriage-virginia-idUSBREA1D05B20140214|accessdate=February 27, 2014 |newspaper=Reuters|date=February 14, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Texas#De Leon v. Perry|Texas]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Calkins|first= Laurel|title= Texas Gay-Marriage Ban Held Illegal as Judge Delays Order|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-02-26/texas-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional-federal-judge-says.html|accessdate=February 27, 2014  |newspaper=Bloomberg|date=February 27, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Michigan#DeBoer v. Snyder|Michigan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww2.lgbtqnation.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Friedman-Michigan-Decision.pdf|title=Deboer v. Snyder: Findings of Fact and Conclusions of Law |publisher=United States District Court for the Eastern District of Michigan Southern Division |date=March 15, 2014 |accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Idaho#Federal lawsuit|Idaho]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Staff reports|first=|title=Federal court strikes down Idaho gay marriage ban|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2014/05/federal-court-strikes-down-idaho-ban-on-same-sex-marriage/|accessdate=May 13, 2014|newspaper=LGBTQ Nation|date=May 13, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Oregon#Federal lawsuit|Oregon]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Federal judge strikes down Oregon's same-sex marriage ban|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/05/19/us/oregon-same-sex-marriage/|publisher=CNN|date=May 19, 2014|accessdate=July 21, 2014|first=Bill|last=Mears |first2=Catherine|last2=Shoichet}}</ref> [[Whitewood v. Corbett|Pennsylvania]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/judge-strikes-down-pennsylvania-same-sex-marriage-ban-n110061|title=Judge Strikes Down Pennsylvania Same-Sex Marriage Ban|publisher=[[NBCNews.com]]|first=Pete |last=Williams|date=May 20, 2014|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref> [[Wolf v. Walker|Wisconsin]],<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/06/06/wisconsin-same-sex-marriage/10093565/ | title=Judge strikes down Wisconsin same-sex marriage ban | publisher=[[USA Today]] | agency=Associated Press | date=June 6, 2014 | accessdate=June 6, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Indiana#Baskin v. Bogan|Indiana]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-judge-strikes-down-indiana-ban-on-gay-marriage-20140625-story.html |title=Judge strikes down Indiana's ban on gay marriage | publisher=Los Angeles Times | author=Javier Panzar | date=June 25, 2014 | accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Kentucky#Bourke v. Beshear / Love v. Beshear|Kentucky]],<ref name="wolfson-ky">{{cite news |last1=Wolfson |first1=Andrew|title=Gays have right to marry in Kentucky, judge rules |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/local/2014/07/01/gays-right-marry-kentucky-judge-rules/11900313/ |accessdate=July 1, 2014|work=The Courier-Journal |date=July 1, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Colorado#Burns v. Hickenlooper|Colorado]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/judge-strikes-gay-marriage-ban-stays-ruling-24687448|title=Judge Strikes Down Gay Marriage Ban, Stays Ruling|accessdate=July 23, 2014|publisher=[[ABC News]] |agency=Associated Press|date=July 23, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Florida|Florida]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Rothaus |first=Steve|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2014/08/21/4301754/federal-judge-florida-gay-marriage.html |title=Federal judge: Florida gay-marriage ban unconstitutional |accessdate=August 21, 2014|publisher=Miami Herald|date=August 21, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in North Carolina#General Synod of the United Church of Christ v. Cooper|North Carolina]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Snow|first1=Justin |title=Federal judge strikes down North Carolina same-sex marriage ban |url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/10/federal-judge-strikes-down-north-carolina-same-sex-marriage-ban/|accessdate=October 10, 2014|work=Metro Weekly|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in Alaska#Hamby v. Parnell|Alaska]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boots |first1=Michelle Theriault|title=Federal judge rules Alaska's same-sex marriage ban unconstitutional |url=http://www.adn.com/article/20141012/federal-judge-rules-alaskas-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional|accessdate=October 13, 2014|work=Alaska Dispatch News|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Wyoming|Wyoming]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Order|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/243372518/2-14-cv-00200-44-Wyoming-Injuntion|website=Scribd.com|publisher=U.S. District Court for Wyoming|accessdate=October 17, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Kansas|Kansas]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Geidner|first1=Chris|title=Federal Judge Strikes Down Kansas Same-Sex Marriage Ban On Election Day|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/federal-judge-strikes-down-kansa