 and K.L.L.]]'' (Texas),<ref>{{cite web|last=Kuffner|first=Charles|title=State court rules gay marriage ban is unconstitutional |url=http://blog.chron.com/kuffsworld/2014/04/state-court-rules-gay-marriage-ban-is-unconstitutional/|publisher=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=May 11, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Same-sex marriage in Colorado#Brinkman v. Long|Brinkman v. Long]]'' (Colorado),<ref>{{cite news|last1=Steffen|first1=Jordan|title=Adams judge tosses Colorado gay marriage ban but stays ruling |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_26118709/adams-judge-tosses-colorado-gay-marriage-ban-but|work=[[The Denver Post]] |date=July 9, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Pareto v. Ruvin]]'' and ''[[Same-sex marriage in Florida|Huntsman v. Heavilin]]'' (Florida),<ref>{{cite news|last1=Associated Press|title=Ruling allows same-sex marriages for Florida Keys|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/07/17/gay-same-sex-marriage-florida-keys/12786169/|work=[[USA Today]]|date=July 17, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Same-sex marriage in Louisiana|In Re Costanza and Brewer]]'' (Louisiana),<ref name=buzzfeed20140922>{{cite news|work=BuzzFeed News|date=September 22, 2014|accessdate=September 22, 2014|first=Chris|last=Geidner|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/louisiana-judge-rules-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional |title= Louisiana Judge Rules Same-Sex Marriage Ban Unconstitutional, Clashing With Federal Court}}</ref> and [[Same-sex marriage in Missouri|Missouri]].}} plus one additional state court limited to rule on the issue as pertaining recognition only,{{efn|See ''[[LGBT rights in Missouri|Barrier v. Vasterling]]'', [[Missouri Circuit Courts|Missouri Circuit Court, 16th Judicial Circuit]], no appeal taken.<ref name="Washington Blade">{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|title=Judge orders Missouri to recognize same-sex marriages |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/10/03/judge-orders-missouri-recognize-sex-marriages/|accessdate=October 3, 2014 |work=Washington Blade|date=October 3, 2014}}</ref>}} have found that same-sex marriage bans violate the [[Constitution of the United States|U.S. Constitution]], while two U.S. district courts{{efn|''[[Robicheaux v. Caldwell]]'' (Louisiana), ''[[LGBT rights in Puerto Rico#Court cases|Conde v. Rius]]'' (Puerto Rico)<ref>{{cite news|last=Associated Press|title=Federal judge upholds La. gay-marriage ban|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/09/03/gay-marriage-louisiana/15021785 |accessdate=September 3, 2014|newspaper=USA Today|date=September 3, 2014}}</ref>}} and one state court{{efn|''[[Recognition of same-sex unions in Tennessee#State lawsuit|''Borman v. Pyles-Borman'']]'' (Tennessee)}} have found that they do not. The [[U.S. Courts of Appeals]] for the [[Same-sex marriage in the Fourth Circuit|Fourth]], [[Same-sex marriage in the Seventh Circuit|Seventh]], [[Same-sex marriage in the Ninth Circuit|Ninth]], and [[Same-sex marriage in the Tenth Circuit|Tenth]] Circuits have affirmed the unconstitutionality of such bans. The [[Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals|Sixth Circuit]], in contrast, did not. The panel reversed six U.S. district court rulings that found bans on same-sex marriage or its recognition unconstitutional in the four states served by the Sixth Circuit.{{efn|The cases reversed (and affected states) are: ''[[Bourke v. Beshear]]'' and ''[[Love v. Beshear]]'' ([[Same-sex marriage in Kentucky|Kentucky]]), ''[[DeBoer v. Snyder]]'' ([[Same-sex marriage in Michigan|Michigan]]), ''[[Obergefell v. Himes]]'' and ''[[Henry v. Himes]]'' ([[Same-sex marriage in Ohio|Ohio]]), and ''[[Tanco v. Haslam]]'' ([[Same-sex marriage in Tennessee|Tennessee]]).}}<ref name="Thomaston">{{cite news|last=Thomaston|first=Scottie|title=Sixth Circuit upholds same-sex marriage bans|url=http://equalityontrial.com/2014/11/06/sixth-circuit-upholds-sex-marriage-bans/|accessdate=November 6, 2014|date=November 6, 2014}}</ref> Most court-ordered [[injunction]]s that enforce the right to same-sex marriage, where the court has ruled in favor of such, have taken effect. The exceptions are the several cases on appeal in Texas,{{efn|''[[De Leon v. Perry]]'' in the U.S. Fifth Circuit, and ''[[In re Marriage of J.B. and H.B.]]'' and ''[[Same-sex marriage in Texas#In the Matter of the Marriage of A.L.F.L. and K.L.L.|In the Matter of the Marriage of A.L.F.L. and K.L.L.]]'' in the state appellate system.}} the Missouri case on appeal in the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit|Eighth Circuit]],{{efn|''[[Lawson v. Kelly]]''}} several cases in the Florida state court system,{{efn|''[[Pareto v. Ruvin]]'' and ''[[Same-sex marriage in Florida|Huntsman v. Heavilin]]'', among others.}} and a case taken to the Arkansas Supreme Court{{efn|''[[Wright v. Arkansas]]''}}—those have been stayed indefinitely. A temporary stay is currently in effect on Florida case in the Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals.{{efn|''[[Brenner v. Armstrong]]'', while on appeal to the U.S. Eleventh Circuit. Set to expire on January 5, 2015.}}

On October 6, 2014, the U.S. Supreme Court declined to hear appeals in all the cases it had been asked to consider from appellate courts in the [[Same-sex marriage in the Fourth Circuit|Fourth]], [[Same-sex marriage in the Seventh Circuit|Seventh]], and [[Same-sex marriage in the Tenth Circuit|Tenth]] Circuits, allowing decisions from those courts striking down marriage bans to stand. The states with bans at issue in those cases were Indiana, Oklahoma, Utah, Virginia, and Wisconsin. The court's action has also led to legal same-sex marriage in Colorado, Kansas, North Carolina, South Carolina, West Virginia, and Wyoming.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Robert|title=Supreme Court declines to review same-sex marriage cases |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/courts_law/supreme-court-declines-to-review-same-sex-marriage-cases/2014/10/06/ee822848-4d5e-11e4-babe-e91da079cb8a_story.html|accessdate=October 6, 2014|work=Washington Post|date=October 6, 2014}}</ref> A decision on October 7, 2014, by the [[Same-sex marriage in the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit]] invalidating bans on same-sex marriage in Idaho and Nevada has affected Alaska,<ref name=NYTalaska>{{cite news|work=New York Times| date= October 12, 2014| accessdate= October 12, 2014| url= http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2014/10/12/us/ap-us-gay-marriage-alaska.html |title=Federal Judge Strikes Down Alaska's Marriage Ban | agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Arizona,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|title=Court strikes down Arizona ban on same-sex marriage|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/10/17/court-strikes-arizona-ban-sex-marriage/|accessdate=October 17, 2014|work=Washington Blade|date=October 17, 2014}}</ref> and Montana;<ref name=bladeMT/> it is expected to affect Guam, and the Northern Mariana Islands as well.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wolf|first1=Richard|title=More gay marriage bans fall in Idaho and Nevada |url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/10/07/federal-appeals-court-gay-marriage-idaho-nevada/16872117/|accessdate=October 7, 2014|work=USA Today|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref>

On November 6, 2014, the Sixth Circuit became the first federal appellate court to uphold same-sex marriage bans since the ''Windsor'' decision.

==Legal issues==
{{See also|Same-sex marriage legislation in the United States}}
[[File:Same-sex marriage in San Francisco City Hall 20080617.jpg|thumb|right|Civil [[same-sex marriage]] ceremony being performed in [[San Francisco]] [[San Francisco City Hall|City Hall]] in June 2008.]]
The legal issues surrounding same-sex marriage in the United States are determined by the nation's [[federalism|federal]] system of government, in which the [[Status (law)|status]] of a person, including marital status, is determined in large measure by the individual states. Prior to 1996, the federal government did not define marriage; any marriage recognized by a [[U.S. state|state]] was recognized by the federal government, even if that marriage was not recognized by one or more states, as was the case until 1967 with interracial marriage which some states [[anti-miscegenation laws|banned by statute]].

===Federal law===
The [[Defense of Marriage Act]] (DOMA) was enacted in 1996. DOMA's Section 2 says that no state need recognize the legal validity of a same-sex relationship even if recognized as marriage by another state. It purports to relieve a state of its reciprocal obligation to honor the laws of other states as required by the Constitution's [[full faith and credit clause]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wermiel|first1=Stephen|title=SCOTUS for law students: The Defense of Marriage Act and the Constitution|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2012/03/scotus-for-law-students-the-defense-of-marriage-act-and-the-constitution-sponsored-by-bloomberg-law/|accessdate=September 23, 2014|work=SCOTUSblog |date=March 23, 2012}}</ref> Even before DOMA, however, states sometimes refused to recognize a marriage from another jurisdiction if it was counter to its "strongly held public policies".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolff|first1=Tobias Barrington|title=DOMA Repeal and the Truth About Full Faith & Credit |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tobias-barrington-wolff/doma-repeal-and-the-truth_b_905484.html |accessdate=September 23, 2014|work=Huffington Post|date=July 21, 2011}}</ref> Most lawsuits that seek to require a state to recognize a marriage established in another jurisdiction argue on the basis of [[equal protection clause|equal protection]] and [[due process clause|due process]], not the full faith and credit clause.{{efn|Among many examples: (1) the U.S. District Court ruling in ''[[Bourke v. Beshear]]'', which required Kentucky to recognize same-sex marriages from Canada and several U.S. states, was decided on equal protection grounds alone. The plaintiffs had claimed that Kentucky's ban violated the full faith and credit clause, but the court found it unnecessary to address that argument.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/206724639/GREGORY-BOURKE-et-al-V-STEVE-BESHEAR-et-al |title=Memorandum Opinion, ''Bouke v. Beshear''|publisher= U.S. District Court for the Western District of Kentucky |date=February 12, 2014}}</ref> and (2) the plaintiffs in ''[[Robicheaux v. Caldwell]]'', who sought Louisiana's recognition of their out-of-state marriages, argued only on the basis of equal protection and due process. One of the Louisiana statutes they challenged made clear the state's assertion of its right to deny recognition to the legal act of another state: "A purported marriage between persons of the same sex violates a ''strong public policy'' of the state of Louisiana". (emphasis added)  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/238549858/2-13-cv-05090-131 |title=Order and Reasons, ''Robicheaux v. Caldwell''|publisher= U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Louisiana |date=September 3, 2014}}</ref> }}

DOMA's Section 3 defined marriage for the purposes of federal law as a union of one man and one woman.<ref>{{usc|1|7}}.</ref> It was challenged in the [[United States federal courts|federal courts]]. On July 8, 2010, Judge [[Joseph Louis Tauro|Joseph Tauro]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts|District Court of Massachusetts]] held that the denial of federal rights and benefits to lawfully married Massachusetts same-sex couples is unconstitutional under the [[equal protection clause]] of the [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]].<ref name="hrc.org">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/09/us/09marriage.html|title=Judge Topples U.S. Rejection of Gay Unions|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 8, 2010|accessdate=June 2, 2011|first1=Abby |last1=Goodnough |first2=John|last2=Schwartz}}</ref><ref name="politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com">{{cite news |url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2010/07/09/judge-rules-federal-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional/ |title=Judge rules federal same-sex marriage ban unconstitutional |publisher=CNN|date=July 9, 2010|accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref> Beginning in 2010, eight federal courts found DOMA Section 3 unconstitutional on issues including bankruptcy, public employee benefits, estate taxes, and immigration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freedomtomarry.org/states/entry/c/doma|title=The Defense of Marriage Act|publisher=Freedom to Marry |accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/31/doma-unconstitutional-ruling-appeals-court-boston_n_1559031.html|title=DOMA Ruled Unconstitutional By Federal Appeals Court |last=Lavoie |first=Denise |date=May 31, 2012|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pewstates.org/projects/stateline/headlines/defense-of-marriage-act-discriminates-against-gays-federal-court-rules-85899424320|title=Defense of Marriage Act Discriminates Against Gays, Federal Court Rules|last=Malewitz|first=Jim|date=October 18, 2012 |publisher=Pewstates.org|accessdate=October 20, 2012}}</ref> On October 18, 2012, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|Second Circuit Court of Appeals]] became the first court<ref>{{cite web|last=Tiven|first=Rachel|title=Edie Wins! Another Ruling Against DOMA, What It Means|url=http://www.immigrationequality.org/2012/10/edie-wins-another-ruling-against-doma-what-it-means/|publisher=[[Immigration Equality (organization)]]|accessdate=October 23, 2012}}</ref> to hold sexual orientation to be a [[suspect classification|quasi-suspect classification]] and applied [[intermediate scrutiny]] to strike down Section 3 of DOMA as unconstitutional in ''[[Windsor v. United States]]''.<ref>[http://www.ca2.uscourts.gov/decisions/isysquery/1afe4f62-fbf9-4e0d-a409-26ab7396971e/1/doc/12-2335_complete_opn.pdf ''Windsor v. United States''], 12-2335-cv(L), October 18, 2012.</ref> Asked to consider several cases that found DOMA Section 3 unconstitutional, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in ''Windsor'' on June 26, 2013, that Section 3 violated the Fifth Amendment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Live Analysis of the Supreme Court Decisions on Gay Marriage|url=http://projects.nytimes.com/live-dashboard/2013-06-26-supreme-court-gay-marriage|accessdate=June 26, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 26, 2013}}</ref>{{efn|Other cases that sought review by the U.S. Supreme Court were ''[[Golinski v. Office of Personnel Management]]'', ''[[Gill v. Office of Personnel Management]]'', ''[[Massachusetts v. United States Department of Health and Human Services]]'', and ''[[Pedersen v. Office of Personnel Management]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Geidner|first=Chris|title=DOJ Asks Supreme Court to Take Two DOMA Cases, Maintains Law Is Unconstitutional |url=http://www.metroweekly.com/poliglot/2012/07/breaking-doj-asks-supreme-court-to-take-two-doma-c.html|accessdate=July 19, 2012|newspaper=Metro Weekly|date=July 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shapiro|first=Lila|title=Edie Windsor vs. DOMA: 83-Year-Old Lesbian Petitions U.S. Supreme Court To Hear Case|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/16/edie-windsor-doma_n_1675983.html|accessdate=July 19, 2012|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=July 16, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Grindley|first=Lucas|title=Republicans Appeal DOMA Case to Supreme Court|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/marriage-equality/2012/06/29/republicans-appeal-doma-case-supreme-court|accessdate=July 19, 2012|newspaper=The Advocate|date=June 19, 2012}}</ref>}}

As a result of the ''Windsor'' decision, married same-sex couples–regardless of domicile–have tax benefits (including the ability to file joint federal income tax returns), military benefits, federal employment benefits for employees of the [[United States Government|U.S Government]] and immigration benefits.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Michon|first1=Kathleen|title=Federal Marriage Benefits Available to Same-Sex Couples|url=http://www.nolo.com/legal-encyclopedia/same-sex-couples-federal-marriage-benefits-30326.html|accessdate=July 26, 2014|publisher=Nolo.com a.k.a. Nolo Law for all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Laurence |first1=Beth|title=Military Benefits for Same-Sex Spouses Post-DOMA|url=http://www.nolo.com/legal-encyclopedia/military-benefits-same-sex-spouses-post-doma.html|publisher=Nolo.com a.k.a. Nolo Law for all|accessdate=July 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wadsworth|first1=Margaret|title=Veterans Benefits for Same-Sex Spouses Post-DOMA|url=http://www.nolo.com/legal-encyclopedia/veterans-benefits-same-sex-spouses-post-doma.html|publisher=Nolo.com a.k.a. Nolo Law for all |accessdate=July 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=John Kerry Announces Visa Changes for Same-Sex Couples |url=http://blogs.usembassy.gov/malaysia/2013/08/05/john-kerry-announces-visa-changes-for-same-sex-couples/ |publisher=U.S. Embassy Kuala Lumpur|accessdate=July 26, 2014|date=August 2, 2013}}</ref> In February 2014, the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] expanded recognition of same-sex marriages in federal legal matters, including bankruptcies, prison visits, survivor benefits and the legal right to refuse to testify to incriminate a spouse.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perez |first1=Evan|title=U.S. expands legal benefits, services for same-sex marriages|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/02/08/politics/holder-same-sex-marriage-rights/|publisher=CNN|accessdate=July 26, 2014|date=February 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Holder, Jr.|first1=Eric|title=Office of Attorney Memorandum to all department employees entitled ''Department Policy on Ensuring Equal Treatment for Same-Sex Married Couples''|url=http://www.justice.gov/iso/opa/resources/9201421014257314255.pdf |publisher=U.S. Department of Justice|accessdate=July 26, 2014|date=February 10, 2014}}</ref> Likewise in June 2014, family [[medical leave]] benefits under the ''Family Medical Leave Act 1975'' were extended to married same-sex couples in all of the U.S.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chappell|first1=Bill|title=Married Same-Sex Couples To Receive More Federal Benefits |url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/06/20/323855724/same-sex-couples-across-u-s-to-receive-broader-benefits |accessdate=July 26, 2014|work=National Public Radio|date=June 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Guardian20140620" /> With respect to [[social security]] and veterans benefits, same-sex married couples who live in states where same-sex marriage is recognized are eligible for full benefits from the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veterans Affairs]] (VA) and the [[Social Security Administration]] (SSA). The VA and SSA can provide only limited benefits to married same-sex couples living in states where same-sex marriage isn't legal, with [[United States Congress|Congress]] required to amend federal law to rectify that inequity.<ref name="Guardian20140620">{{cite news|last1=Glenza|first1=Jessica|title=Federal agencies roll out benefits for married same-sex couples|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/20/same-sex-couples-benefits-expanded-obama-administration|accessdate=July 26, 2014|work=The Guardian|publisher=The Guardian|date=June 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Capehart|first1=Jonathan|title=Fix the Social Security discrepancy DOMA left behind |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-partisan/wp/2014/05/09/fix-the-social-security-discrepancy-doma-left-behind/ |accessdate=July 26, 2014|work=The Washington Post|date=May 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Capehart |first1=Jonathan |title=Social Security agency shows why Supreme Court must act on gay marriage|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-partisan/wp/2014/06/23/social-security-agency-shows-why-supreme-court-must-act-on-gay-marriage/|accessdate=July 26, 2014 |work=The Washington Post|date=June 23, 2014}}</ref>

The federal government has announced that it recognizes the marriages of same-sex couples who married in certain states in which same-sex marriage was legal for brief periods between the time a court order allowed such couples to marry and that court order was stayed, including Michigan and Utah. It has yet to take a position with respect to similar marriages in Arkansas, Indiana, and Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|title=DOJ pressured to recognize same-sex marriages in 3 states|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/09/19/doj-pressured-recognize-sex-marriages-3-states/|accessdate=September 24, 2014|work=Washington Blade|date=September 19, 2014}}</ref>

According to the federal government's [[Government Accountability Office]] (GAO) in 2004, [[Rights and responsibilities of marriages in the United States|more than 1,138 rights and protections]] are conferred to U.S. citizens upon marriage by the federal government; areas affected include [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] benefits, veterans' benefits, health insurance, [[Medicaid]], hospital visitation, estate taxes, retirement savings, [[pension]]s, [[family leave]], and immigration law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d04353r.pdf|title=2004 updated report of the GAO|format=PDF|date=January 23, 2004|accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref>

In 1972, the U.S. Supreme Court declined an appeal in ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'', a same-sex marriage case from Minnesota, "for want of a substantial federal question."<ref>{{cite news|last=Denniston|first=Lyle|title=Gay marriage and Baker v. Nelson|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2012/07/gay-marriage-and-baker-v-nelson/|accessdate=September 14, 2012|newspaper=[[SCOTUSblog]]|date=July 4, 2012}}</ref> The ''Baker'' precedent for many years closed the federal courts to legal advocacy on behalf of same-sex marriage rights. Since the Supreme Court decision in ''Windsor'', however, most federal courts that have considered same-sex marriage cases have held that ''Baker'' is no longer binding precedent, because, as a district judge in Pennsylvania wrote in November 2013, "[t]he jurisprudence of equal protection and substantive due process has undergone what can only be characterized as a sea change since 1972".<ref>{{cite news|last=Warden |first=Amy|title=Judge clears way for trial on Pa. gay marriage ban |url=http://articles.philly.com/2013-11-17/news/44141203_1_marriage-ban-marriage-rights-marriage-act |accessdate=November 18, 2013|newspaper=Philadelphia Inquirer|date=November 17, 2013}}</ref>

Opponents of same-sex marriage have worked to prevent individual states from recognizing same-sex unions by attempting to amend the United States Constitution to define marriage as a union between one man and one woman. In 2006, the [[Federal Marriage Amendment]], which would prohibit states from recognizing same-sex marriages, was approved by the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]] on a party-line vote and was debated by the full Senate, but was ultimately defeated in both houses of Congress.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/POLITICS/06/07/same.sex.marriage/index.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080511145406/http://www.cnn.com/2006/POLITICS/06/07/same.sex.marriage/index.html|title=Senate blocks same-sex marriage ban|publisher=CNN|date=June 7, 2006|archivedate=May 11, 2008|accessdate=July 5, 2006}}</ref> On April 2, 2014, the Alabama State House adopted a resolution calling for a [[Convention to propose amendments to the United States Constitution|constitutional convention]] to propose an amendment to ban same-sex marriage nationwide.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140412171146/http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20140402/NEWS/304020079/Alabama-House-approves-call-put-same-sex-marriage-ban-U-S-Constitution|title=Alabama House approves call to put same-sex marriage ban in U.S. Constitution|publisher=Montgomery Advertiser|date=April 2, 2014|accessdate=April 3, 2014}}</ref>

===State law===
{{Further|Same-sex marriage law in the United States by state}}
{{Samesex marriage in USA map|align=left}}

Prior to 2004, same-sex marriage was not performed in any U.S. jurisdiction. It has since been legalized in different jurisdictions through legislation, court rulings,<ref name="Adams & Crary March 11, 2009">Glenn Adams and David Crary, [http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/feedarticle/8789627 "Maine voters reject gay-marriage law"], November 4, 2009</ref> tribal council rulings,<ref name="LittleTraverseBayBand">{{cite news|last=Houston|first=Sonya|title=Tribe marries same-sex couple but state won't recognize it|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/03/17/politics/michigan-same-sex-marriage/index.html?hpt=hp_c5|accessdate=March 18, 2013|newspaper=CNN|date=March 17, 2013}}</ref> and popular vote in statewide referenda.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbcpolitics.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/11/07/14978747-for-first-time-voters-back-gay-marriage-in-statewide-votes?lite|title=For first time, voters back gay marriage in statewide votes|publisher=NBC News|date=|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usnews.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2012/02/01/10294578-washington-state-senate-approves-same-sex-marriage-bill|title=Washington State Senate approves same-sex marriage|publisher=MSNBC|date=February 1, 2012}}</ref>
<!-- THIS SECTION IS ABOUT THE STATE OF THE LAW AT PRESENT, WHERE SSM IS LEGAL OR NOT LEGAL. IT'S NOT ABOUT THE PROCESS, WHICH IS ELSEWHERE IN THE HISTORICAL NARRATIVE AND LITIGATION SECTIONS -->
As of November 20, 2014, 35 states (Alaska, Arizona, California, Colorado, Connecticut, Delaware, Hawaii, Idaho, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Montana, Nevada, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New Mexico, New York, North Carolina, Oklahoma, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, South Carolina, Utah, Vermont, Virginia, Washington, West Virginia, Wisconsin, and Wyoming) and the District of Columbia issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples and recognize same-sex marriages from other jurisdictions.

Missouri recognizes same-sex marriages established in other jurisdictions.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lippmann|first1=Rachel|title=Koster Will Not Appeal Ruling Ordering State To Recognize Same-Sex Marriages|url=http://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/koster-will-not-appeal-ruling-ordering-state-recognize-same-sex-marriages|accessdate=14 October 2014|work=St. Louis Public Radio|date=October 6, 2014}}</ref> A state court ruling striking down Missouri's same-sex marriage ban required the [[Independent City]] of [[St. Louis]] to issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples. [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]] and [[Jackson County, Missouri|Jackson County]] also issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples. 

A federal court injunction barred the Secretary of the Kansas Department of Health and Environment, [[Douglas County, Kansas|Douglas County]] and [[Sedgwick County, Kansas|Sedgwick County]] from enforcing Kansas's same-sex marriage ban. Seventeen other counties in Kansas also issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples. Most Kansans live in a county that licenses same-sex marriage.

Jurisdictions that neither license same-sex marriages nor recognize same-sex marriages from other jurisdictions include 14 states (Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana, Michigan, Mississippi, Nebraska, North Dakota, Ohio, South Dakota, Tennessee, and Texas), Puerto Rico, and the Virgin Islands.

American Samoa, Guam, and the Northern Mariana Islands do not have any law prohibiting or recognizing same-sex marriage.{{efn|The American Samoa Code Annotated requires the parties to a marriage to identify themselves "son" and "daughter" of their parents and refers to the age of "the male" and "the female".<ref>{{cite web|title=American Samoa Code Annotated, Title 42, Chapter 01 - Marriage|url=http://www.asbar.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=690&Itemid=172 |website=American Samoa Bar Association|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref> The Guam Code Annotated requires that the parties to a marriage "declare in the presence of the person solemnizing the marriage that they take each other as husband and wife."<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=November 5, 2014|url=http://www.guamcourts.org/compileroflaws/GCA/19gca/19gc003.PDF |title=Chapter 3: The Contract of Marriage}}</ref>}} Even with no prohibition, none of these territories recognizes same-sex marriage.

===Tribal law===
{{main|Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions}}
In the United States, federally recognized Native American tribes have the legal right to form their own marriage laws.<ref>{{cite web|author=Joe Shirley, Jr. |url=http://www.freedomtomarry.org/communities/entry/c/native-americans |title=Native Americans |publisher=Freedom to Marry |accessdate=November 13, 2013}}</ref> There are [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions|eleven tribal jurisdictions]] that legally recognize [[same-sex marriage]]: the [[Cheyenne and Arapaho Tribes]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Brandes |first=Heide |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/11/01/us-usa-gaymarriage-oklahoma-idUSBRE9A00JW20131101 |title=Oklahoma gay couple marry under Native American law |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=November 13, 2013 |date=November 1, 2013}}</ref> the [[Confederated Tribes of the Colville Reservation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/2013/sep/07/colvilles-recognize-same-sex-marriage/ |title=Colvilles recognize same sex marriage |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date=September 7, 2013 |accessdate=November 13, 2013}}</ref> the [[Coquille Tribe]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Administrator |url=http://www.americanindianreport.com/wordpress/2008/08/coquille-first-tribe-in-the-country-to-recognize-same-sex-marriage/ |title=Coquille First Tribe in the Country to Recognize Same-Sex Marriage |publisher=American Indian Report |accessdate=November 13, 2013}}</ref> the [[Leech Lake Band of Ojibwe]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Andrew Potts |url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/8th-us-native-american-tribe-allows-same-sex-couples-wed161113 |title=8th US Native American tribe allows same-sex couples to wed |publisher=gaystarnews.com |date=November 16, 2013 |accessdate=November 21, 2013}}</ref> the [[Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nativenewsnetwork.com/little-traverse-bay-bands-of-odawa-indians-to-sign-same-sex-marriage-statute.html |title=Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians to Sign Same Sex Marriage Statute |publisher=nativenewsnetwork.com |accessdate=November 13, 2013}}</ref> the [[Mashantucket Pequot Tribe]],<ref>[http://www.mptnlaw.com/laws/2010-2011%20Pocket%20Part%20to%202008%20Tribal%20Laws.pdf Mashantucket Pequot Tribal Laws Annotated 2010–2011 Pocket Part]</ref> the [[Pokagon Band of Potawatomi Indians]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://michiganradio.org/post/northern-michigan-tribe-legalizes-same-sex-marriage |title=Northern Michigan tribe legalizes same sex marriage |publisher=Michigan Radio |date=March 18, 2013 |accessdate=November 13, 2013}}</ref> the [[Puyallup tribe]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Nagle |first=Matt |url=http://www.tacomaweekly.com/news/view/puyallup-tribe-recognizes-same-sex-marriages/ |title=Puyallup Tribe Recognizes Same-Sex Marriages |publisher=Tacoma Weekly |date=July 16, 2014 |accessdate=July 21, 2014}}</ref> the [[Santa Ysabel Tribe]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiancountrytodaymedianetwork.com/2013/06/28/santa-ysabel-tribe-first-california-support-same-sex-marriage-150179 |title=Santa Ysabel Tribe First in California to Support Same-Sex Marriage |publisher=Indian Country Today Media Network |date=June 28, 2013 |accessdate=November 13, 2013}}</ref> the [[Suquamish tribe]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/12/us/12tribe.html?_r=0|title=A Washington State Indian Tribe Approves Same-Sex Marriage|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=November 13, 2013|first=William|last=Yardley|date=August 11, 2011}}</ref> and the [[Wind River Indian Reservation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianz.com/News/2014/015673.asp |title=Wind River tribal judge presides over first same-sex marriage |publisher=Indianz.Com |date=November 17, 2014 |accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref>

==History==
{{See also|Timeline of same-sex marriage in the United States}}

===Early history===
The [[Minnesota Supreme Court]] ruled in 1971 that Minnesota's laws prohibiting marriages between same-sex partners did not violate the federal constitution. In 1972, the U.S. Supreme Court declined to consider the case, ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'', "for want of a substantial federal question."

In April 1993, as part of the demonstrations surrounding the [[March on Washington for Lesbian, Gay and Bi Equal Rights and Liberation|gay rights march]] in Washington, D.C., about 1,500 same-sex couples staged a mass wedding ceremony with "a dozen ministers, organ music, photographers and rice" at the [[National Museum of Natural History]] to call for marriage rights for gays and lesbians.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wheeler|first1=Linda|title=Mass Wedding Marries Tradition and Protest|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-943527.html|accessdate=October 14, 2014|work=Washington Post|publisher=Highbeam Research|date=April 25, 1993}}</ref>

In 1998, in response to the [[Hawaii Supreme Court]]'s ruling in ''[[Baehr v. Miike]]'', Hawaii voters approved a [[Hawaii Constitutional Amendment 2|state constitutional amendment]] allowing their legislature to ban same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Hawaii Office of Elections|title=General Election 1998|url=http://hawaii.gov/elections/results/1998/general/98swgen.htm|date=November 3, 1998|accessdate=March 2, 2011}}</ref>

The next decade saw lasting change. In 2003, the U.S. Supreme Court struck down Texas' "Homosexual Conduct" law in ''[[Lawrence v. Texas]]''.<ref>{{cite court|litigants=Lawrence v. Texas|vol=539 |reporter=U.S.|opinion=558|date=2003|url=http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/02-102.ZS.html/}}</ref> The ruling rendered unenforceable same-sex sodomy laws in Kansas, Oklahoma and Missouri and broader [[Sodomy laws in the United States|sodomy laws]] in nine other states.<ref>{{cite news|title=High Court Rejects Sodomy Law |last=Schlesinger|first=Richard|date=June 26, 2003|publisher=CBS News|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/06/26/supremecourt/main560508.shtml|quote=Of the 13 states with sodomy laws, four—Texas, Kansas, Oklahoma and Missouri—prohibit oral and anal sex between same-sex couples. The other nine ban consensual sodomy for everyone: Alabama, Florida, Idaho, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, South Carolina, Utah and Virginia. Thursday's ruling apparently invalidates those laws as well.}}</ref>

On November 18, 2003, the [[Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court]] ruled in ''[[Goodridge v. Department of Public Health]]'' that denying marriage rights to same-sex couples violated the state constitution.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2003/11/18/sjc_gay_marriage_legal_in_mass/|title=SJC: Gay marriage legal in Mass. |work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=November 18, 2003|accessdate=June 27, 2010|first1=Kathleen|last1=Burge}}</ref> Massachusetts became the first United States jurisdiction to license and recognize same-sex marriages beginning May 17, 2004.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kathleen|last=Burge| accessdate=September 30, 2014| url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2003/11/18/sjc_gay_marriage_legal_in_mass/ |title=SJC: Gay marriage legal in Mass.|publisher=The Boston Globe|date=November 18, 2003}}</ref>

In February and March 2004, city officials in San Francisco issued marriage licenses to about 4000 same-sex couples before being ordered to stop by the [[California Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Dean E.|last=Murphy|title=San Francisco Forced to Halt Gay Marriages|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/12/us/san-francisco-forced-to-halt-gay-marriages.html |accessdate=September 30, 2014|work=New York Times|date=March 12, 2004}}</ref> On February 20, 2004, the clerk in [[Same-sex marriage in New Mexico#2004|Sandoval County]], New Mexico, issued marriage licenses to same-sex couples for a day until the state attorney general issued an opinion that they were "invalid under state law".<ref>{{cite book|last=Pinello |first=Daniel R.|title=America's Struggle for Same-Sex Marriage |year=226 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521848565 |pages=1–17}}</ref> Similar actions occurred in [[Same-sex marriage in New York#New Paltz marriages|New Paltz]], New York (February 27); [[Same-sex marriage in Oregon#Marriage licenses issued|Multnomah County]], Oregon (March 3); and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in New Jersey#Same-sex marriage|Asbury Park]], New Jersey (March 8).<ref>{{cite book|last=Pinello |first=Daniel R. |title=America's Struggle for Same-Sex Marriage|year=2006 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521848565|page=19}}</ref> On November 2, voters in eleven states–[[Arkansas Constitutional Amendment 3 (2004)|Arkansas]], [[Georgia Constitutional Amendment 1 (2004)|Georgia]], [[Kentucky Constitutional Amendment 1 (2004)|Kentucky]], [[Michigan State Proposal – 04-2 (2004)|Michigan]], [[Mississippi Amendment 1 (2004)|Mississippi]], [[Montana Initiative 96 (2004)|Montana]], [[North Dakota Constitutional Measure 1 (2004)|North Dakota]], [[Ohio State Issue 1 (2004)|Ohio]], [[Oklahoma State Question 711 (2004)|Oklahoma]], [[Oregon Ballot Measure 36 (2004)|Oregon]], and [[Utah Constitutional Amendment 3|Utah]]–approved state constitutional amendments defining marriage as the union of one man and one woman.<ref>{{cite news|first=Joel|last=Roberts |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/09/30/politics/main646662.shtml |agency=Associated Press|title=11 States Ban Same-Sex Marriage |publisher=CBS News |date=November 2, 2004 |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref>

On May 15, 2008, the [[Supreme Court of California]] issued a decision that legalized same-sex marriage in California, holding that California's existing opposite-sex definition of marriage violated the constitutional rights of same-sex couples.<ref name="mercury_mintz">{{cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/breakingnews/ci_9269719|title=California Supreme Court legalizes same-sex marriage |last=Mintz|first=Howard|date=May 15, 2008|publisher=Mercury News|accessdate=May 15, 2008}}</ref> To overturn the decision, opponents of same-sex marriage placed a state constitutional amendment on the November ballot.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McKinley|first1=Jesse|title=Gay Couples Rejoice at Ruling|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/16/us/15cnd-scene.html |accessdate=September 30, 2014|work=New York Times|date=May 16, 2008}}</ref> Known as [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Proposition 8]], it passed in November 2008, as did similar marriage-restriction amendments in Florida and Arizona.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McKinley|first1=Jesse|first2=Laurie|last2=Goodstein|title=Bans in 3 States on Gay Marriage |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/06/us/politics/06marriage.html|accessdate=September 30, 2014|work=New York Times|date=November 5, 2008}}</ref> Thus gay marriage started and stopped in California in 2008.

On August 4, 2010, a decision by the U.S. District Court in ''[[Perry v. Schwarzenegger]]'' ruled that Proposition 8 was unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite court|litigants=Perry v. Schwarzenegger|court=US District Court, Northern California|date=August 4, 2010|url=http://www.scribd.com/goodasyou/d/35374462-California-Prop-8-Ruling-August-2010}}</ref> The decision in that case was upheld at appeal and – as the State of California decided not to appeal or defend Proposition 8 – the voters who initially instigated the initiative appealed to the Supreme Court, which asked to be briefed for arguments concerning the appellants' [[standing]], and heard oral arguments on March 26, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.supremecourt.gov/Search.aspx?FileName=/docketfiles/12-144.htm|title=''Hollingsworth v. Perry'', Proceedings and Orders|publisher=[[Supreme Court of the United States]]|accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref> The Supreme Court dismissed the case for lack of standing on June 26, 2013,<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/08/us/supreme-court-agrees-to-hear-two-cases-on-gay-marriage.html "Justices to Hear Two Challenges on Gay Marriage"]. ''New York Times''. December 7, 2012. Retrieved December 8, 2012. (archived at http://www.webcitation.org/6ClunjOCb)</ref> after which same-sex marriage once again became legal in California.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ksbw.com/politics/live-coverage-prop-8-struck-down-by-supreme-court/20722962#ixzz2XL5pPMdU |title=Supreme Court strikes down Calif. Prop 8, DOMA|publisher=Ksbw.com|date=June 26, 2013|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref> Same-sex marriages resumed on June 28, 2013.<ref name="blog.sfgate.com">{{cite news|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/stew/2013/06/28/prop-8-officially-out-sf-weddings-begin/|title=Prop. 8 officially out — SF weddings begin|work=SF Gate|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>

On October 10, 2008, the [[Connecticut Supreme Court]] ruled that the state's civil unions statute discriminated against same-sex couples and required the state to recognize same-sex marriages.<ref>{{cite news|last=McFadden|first=Robert|title=Gay Marriage Is Ruled Legal in Connecticut|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/11/nyregion/11marriage.html |accessdate=July 19, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 10, 2008}}</ref> On November 12, 2008, the first marriage licenses to same-sex couples were issued and the following year, the state enacted gender-neutral marriage legislation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cga.ct.gov/2009/act/Pa/pdf/2009PA-00013-R00SB-00899-PA.PDF|title=Public Act No. 09-13|publisher=Connecticut General Assembly (April 23, 2009)}}</ref>

On April 3, 2009, a unanimous [[Iowa Supreme Court]] ruling upheld a lower court ruling in ''[[Varnum v. Brien]]'' that denying marriage rights to same-sex couples violated the state constitution,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eckhoff|first1=Jeff|last2=Schulte |first2=Grant|title=Unanimous ruling: Iowa marriage no longer limited to one man, one woman |url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20090403/NEWS/90403010 |accessdate=September 30, 2014|work=Des Moines Register |date=April 3, 2009}}</ref> and licenses became available on April 27.<ref name="365gay.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.365gay.com/news/iowa-gay-marriages-delayed/|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090410054756/http://www.365gay.com/news/iowa-gay-marriages-delayed/|archivedate=April 10, 2009|title=Iowa gay marriages delayed |publisher=365gay.com|date=April 7, 2009|accessdate=June 27, 2010}}</ref>

On December 18, 2009, the [[Council of the District of Columbia]] enacted legislation legalizing same-sex marriage<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrcbackstory.org/2009/12/mayor-adrian-fenty-signs-dc-marriage-bill/|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110727225237/http://www.hrcbackstory.org/2009/12/mayor-adrian-fenty-signs-dc-marriage-bill/|archivedate=July 27, 2011|title=Mayor Adrian Fenty Signs DC Marriage Bill|publisher=Hrcbackstory.org|date=December 18, 2009|accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref> and same-sex marriage licenses became available on March 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|author=Post Store|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/gallery/2010/03/03/GA2010030301385.html|title=D.C. same-sex marriage law takes effect|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 3, 2010|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref>

By 2009, [[New England]] became the center of an organized campaign to legalize same-sex marriage.<ref>''[[The Washington Times]]'': [http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/jan/04/gay-marriage-backers-target-new-england/ Valerie Richardson, "Gay marriage backers target New England," January 4, 2009]. Retrieved March 21, 2011</ref> On April 7, 2009, Vermont legalized same-sex marriage through legislation. The Governor of Vermont had previously vetoed the measure, but the veto was overridden by the Legislature. Vermont was the first state in the United States to legalize same-sex marriage through legislative means rather than litigation. On May 6, 2009, Maine Governor [[John Baldacci]] signed a law legalizing same-sex marriage, becoming the first state governor to do so.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.maine.gov/tools/whatsnew/index.php?topic=Gov+News&id=72146&v=Article-2006|title=Governor Signs LD 1020, An Act to End Discrimination in Civil Marriage and Affirm Religious Freedom|publisher=Maine.gov|date=May 6, 2009|accessdate=June 27, 2010}}</ref> Nonetheless, the legislation was stayed pending a vote and never went into effect. It was repealed by referendum in November 2009.<ref name="Adams & Crary March 11, 2009" /> On June 3, 2009, New Hampshire became the sixth state nationally to legalize same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gencourt.state.nh.us/legislation/2009/HB0436.html|title=House Bill 0436|publisher=Gencourt.state.nh.us |date=March 26, 2009|accessdate=June 27, 2010}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Rhode Island|Rhode Island]] legalized same-sex marriage in 2013, the sixth and last state in that region to do so.

In September 2009, when several Democratic members of Congress proposed [[Respect for Marriage Act|legislation to repeal DOMA]], [[Barney Frank]] opposed the move because he thought its enactment impossible.<ref>{{cite news|title=Frank won't back Marriage Act repeal|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/glennthrush/0909/Frank_wont_back_Marriage_Act_repeal.html |accessdate=September 28, 2014|work=Politico|date=September 13, 2009}}</ref> [[Nancy Pelosi]] had warned earlier in the year that the legislative calendar had no room for the issue.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bajko|first1=Matthew S.|title=DOMA repeal unlikely in ’09|url=http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=&sc2=news&sc3=&id=90428|accessdate=September 28, 2014|work=EDGE Boston|date=April 28, 2009}}</ref>

===2010–2012===
{{As of|2010|January}}, 29 states had constitutional provisions restricting marriage to one man and one woman, while 12 others had statutes that did so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org/documents/marriage_prohibitions_2009.pdf|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110728024900/http://www.hrc.org/documents/marriage_prohibitions_2009.pdf|archivedate=July 28, 2011|title=Statewide Marriage Prohibitions|publisher=Human Rights Campaign|date=|accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref> Nineteen states banned any legal recognition of same-sex unions that would be equivalent to civil marriage.<ref>[http://www.hrc.org/documents/marriage_prohibitions_2009.pdf Statewide Marriage Prohibitions] plus Kansas http://www.kslib.info/constitution/art15.html</ref> Voters approved 28 out of 30 [[popular referendum|popular referenda]] in which states asked voters to adopt a constitutional amendment or initiative defining marriage as the union of a man and a woman.{{efn|Alabama, Alaska, Arkansas, California, Colorado, Florida, Georgia, Idaho, Kansas, Kentucky, Louisiana, Michigan, Mississippi, Missouri, Montana, Nebraska, Nevada, North Dakota, Ohio, Oklahoma, Oregon, South Carolina, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Utah, Virginia, Wisconsin. See [[Same-sex marriage legislation in the United States#Attempts to establish same-sex unions via initiative or statewide referendum|Attempts to establish same-sex unions via initiative or statewide referendum]]}} Arizonans voted down [[Arizona Proposition 107 (2006)|one such amendment in 2006]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azsos.gov/election/2006/General/ElectionInformation.htm|title=Arizona Secretary of State: 2006 general election results|accessdate=March 2, 2011}}</ref> but approved [[Arizona Proposition 102 (2008)|a different amendment to that effect]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.azsos.gov/election/2008/General/Canvass2008GE.pdf|title=State of Arizona Official Canvass: 2008 General Election – November 4, 2008|date=December 1, 2008|accessdate=March 2, 2011|format=PDF|publisher=Secretary of State of Arizona}}</ref> In 2012, [[Minnesota]] became the second state to reject [[Minnesota Amendment 1|an amendment]] to its state constitution banning same-sex marriage.<ref name="Startribune">{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/177666881.html?refer=y&vi_adid=W| title=Same-sex marriage ban defeated| date=November 7, 2012|work=StarTribune}}</ref> A bill that would have legalized same-sex marriage in [[Recognition of same-sex unions in New Jersey|New Jersey]] was vetoed by Governor [[Chris Christie]] on February 17, 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|title=N.J. Gov. Christie vetoes gay marriage bill as vowed|url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/story/2012-02-17/gay-marriage-new-jersey/53136648/1|date=February 17, 2012|work=[[USA Today]]|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=February 17, 2012}}</ref>

Prior to the November 2012 election, Maryland recognized same-sex marriages formed in other jurisdictions, but did not license such marriages.<ref name="freedomtomarry1">{{cite web|url=http://www.freedomtomarry.org/states/|title=States|publisher=Freedom to Marry|date=April 16, 2010|accessdate=June 27, 2010}}</ref> Similarly, New York did not issue marriage license to same-sex couples but its courts had mandated the recognition of same-sex marriages established elsewhere,<ref>[http://www.nycourts.gov/courts/ad4/Clerk/Decisions/2008/02-01-08/PDF/1562.pdf Martinez, Patricia v County Of Monroe] Decision Appellate Division Fourth Judicial Department</ref> a situation which changed when its legislature legalized same-sex marriage in 2011.

On May 8, 2012, [[North Carolina]] voters approved a [[North Carolina Senate Bill 514 (2011)|constitutional amendment]] banning same-sex marriage as well as all other types of same-sex unions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2012/primaries/states/north-carolina |title=North Carolina Republican Primary – Election Results |publisher=elections.nytimes.com |accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/post/north-carolina-passes-gay-marriage-ban-amendment-one/2012/05/08/gIQAHYpfBU_blog.html |title=North Carolina passes gay marriage ban Amendment One |publisher=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 25, 2013 |first=Rachel |last=Weiner |date=May 8, 2012}}</ref> North Carolina already prohibited same-sex marriages by statute.

In the regular November 2012 elections, voters for the first time approved the legalization of same-sex marriage by popular vote in three states: [[Same-sex marriage in Maine|Maine]], [[Same-sex marriage in Maryland|Maryland]], and [[Same-sex marriage in Washington|Washington]]. Maine's law took effect on December 29, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/30/us/same-sex-marriage-becomes-legal-in-maine.html|title=A Festive Mood in Maine as Same-Sex Marriage Becomes Legal|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 13, 2013|date=December 29, 2012}}</ref> Maryland started allowing same-sex marriages on January 1, 2013,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2012/11/07/maryland-upholds-same-sex-marriage-law/|title=Maryland upholds same-sex marriage law|publisher=politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com|date=November 7, 2012|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> In Washington state, the first licenses were distributed on December 6, with the first marriages on December 9 following the mandatory three day waiting period.<ref>''[[The Seattle Times]]'': [http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2017497028_gaymarriage14m.html Lornet Turnbull, "Gregoire signs gay marriage into law," February 13, 2012]. Retrieved February 13, 2012</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Turnbull|first=Lornet |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019621744_elexgaymarriage07m.html|title=Gay-marriage measure passing in initial return|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref> In the same election, [[Same-sex marriage in Minnesota|Minnesota]] became the second state to reject a statewide constitutional ban against same-sex marriage by a popular vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vote.wa.gov/results/current/Referendum-Measure-No-74-Concerns-marriage-for-same-sex-couples.html|title=Referendum Measure No. 74 Concerns marriage for same-sex couples|publisher=Washington Secretary of State|date=November 6, 2012|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>

===2013===
Several jurisdictions enacted same-sex marriage in 2013. The [[Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians|Little Traverse Bay Band of Odawa Indians]] of Michigan voted in March 2013 to legalize same-sex marriages under their tribal jurisdiction, although the state maintained that it would not recognize the marriages.<ref name="LittleTraverseBayBand" /> [[Same-sex marriage in Rhode Island|Rhode Island]] enacted legislation on May 2, which took effect August 1;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2013/05/02/rhode-island-legalizes-same-sex-marriage/|title=Rhode Island legalizes same-sex marriage|publisher=Fox News| agency=Associated Press|date=May 2, 2013|accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref> Delaware enacted legislation on May 7, which took effect July 1;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/08/us/delaware-to-allow-same-sex-marriage.html|title=Delaware, Continuing a Trend, Becomes the 11th State to Allow Same-Sex Unions|work=The New York Times|date=May 7, 2013|accessdate=November 2, 2013|first=Erik|last=Eckholm}}</ref> and Minnesota enacted legislation on May 14, which took effect August 1.<ref>{{cite news|last=June|first=Daniel|title=Minnesota Legalizes Same Sex Marriages |url=http://www.jdjournal.com/2013/05/15/minnesota-legalizes-same-sex-marriages/|accessdate=May 15, 2013|newspaper=JD Journal|date=May 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/statelocal/207313571.html?page=all&prepage=1&c=y#continue|title=Minnesota to become 12th state to legalize gay marriage|work=StarTribune|date=May 13, 2013|accessdate=May 14, 2013|author=Helgeson, Baird|location=Minneapolis|author2=Ragsdale, Jim}}</ref> In July 2013, a court clerk in [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]], began issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples, with the rationale that the state marriage statutes were unconstitutional, but his action was overruled by a state [[Pennsylvania Commonwealth Court|intermediate appellate court]] in September and he was ordered to cease issuing the licenses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pacourts.us/assets/files/setting-3220/file-3052.pdf?cb=851383|title=Memorandum Opinion by President Judge Pellegrini|publisher=''Pa. Dept. of Health v. Hanes'', Pa. Commonwealth Ct., Docket 379 M.D. 2013 (September 12, 2013)}}</ref>

New Jersey began issuing same-sex marriage licenses on October 21, 2013, following a September 27 state superior court decision that found an [[Equal Protection Clause|equal protection]] right of same-sex couples to marry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/28/nyregion/new-jersey-judge-rules-state-must-allow-gay-marriage.html|title=Judge Orders New Jersey to Allow Gay Marriage|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 13, 2013|first1=Kate|last1=Zernike |first2=Marc|last2=Santora|date=September 27, 2013}}</ref> Governor [[Chris Christie]] filed an appeal to the New Jersey Supreme Court, but withdrew it after the court declined to stay the lower court's ruling.<ref>{{cite news|title=NJ Gov. Christie drops gay marriage appeal|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/us/article/NJ-Gov-Christie-drops-gay-marriage-appeal-4912296.php|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref>

In October and November 2013, the Hawaii legislature enacted legislation legalizing same-sex marriage, which Governor [[Neil Abercrombie]] signed on November 13. The [[Same-sex marriage in Hawaii#Same-sex marriage legislation (2013)|law took effect]] on December 2, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ian |first=Scheuring|title=Bill legalizing same-sex marriages in Hawaii signed into law |url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/23960302/breaking-gov-abercrombie-signs |accessdate=November 13, 2013|newspaper=Hawaii News Now|date=November 13, 2013}}</ref> The [[Illinois General Assembly]] passed a bill legalizing same-sex marriage on November 5, 2013. The House of Representatives narrowly passed an amended version of an earlier Senate bill 61–54–2 with the Senate approving the House version 32–21 only about an hour later. Governor [[Pat Quinn (politician)|Pat Quinn]] signed the legislation on November 20.<ref>{{cite news|last=Garcia|first=Monique |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-illinois-gay-marriage-bill-signing-20131120,0,4464600.story |title=Quinn signs Illinois gay marriage bill|work=Chicago Tribune |date=November 20, 2013 |accessdate=November 20, 2013}}</ref> On February 21, 2014 [[United States district court|U.S District Judge]] Sharon Johnson Coleman ruled that same-sex couples in [[Cook County, Illinois|Cook County]], which includes Illinois' largest city [[Chicago]], can obtain marriage licenses immediately and need not wait until the law's June 1 effective date.<ref>{{cite news |title=Same-sex couples allowed to wed in Cook County, Illinois |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/02/21/us-usa-gaymarriage-illinois-idUSBREA1K1MC20140221|accessdate=February 21, 2014|publisher=Reuters |date=February 21, 2014}}</ref> On February 26, 2014, a [[Champaign County, Illinois|Champaign County]] clerk began issuing same-sex marriage licenses after consulting the State's Attorney and concluding that the Cook County order is applicable.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-02-26/news/chi-champaign-county-begins-issuing-samesex-marriage-licenses-20140226_1_issuing-marriage-licenses-bernard-cherkasov-equality-illinois |title=Champaign County begins issuing same-sex marriage licenses |work=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=February 27, 2014 |date=February 26, 2014}}</ref>

In 2013, certain New Mexico counties, either on the basis of a court decision or their clerks' own volition, began issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples. In August 2013, [[Doña Ana County, New Mexico|Doña Ana County]]<ref>{{cite news|title=New Mexico county begins issuing same-sex marriage licenses amid pending court battles |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/southern-nm-county-to-issue-same-sex-marriage-licenses-amid-pending-court-battles/2013/08/21/e04b3878-0a8e-11e3-89fe-abb4a5067014_story.html|accessdate=August 21, 2013|newspaper=Washington Post|date=August 21, 2013|deadurl=yes}} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> and [[Santa Fe County, New Mexico|Santa Fe County]] began issuing same-sex marriage licenses, the latter through a court order.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://judgepedia.org/index.php/Sarah_M._Singleton|title=Sarah M. Singleton |publisher=Judgepedia|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfreporter.com/santafe/blog-4746-judge-orders-sf-county-clerk-to-issue-same-sex-marriage-licenses.html|title=Updated: Santa Fe County Clerk to begin issuing same-sex marriage licenses Friday at 2pm|publisher=Sfreporter.com|date=August 23, 2013|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-same-sex-new-mexico-20130823,0,2716948.story |title=Second New Mexico county now issuing same-sex marriage licenses|last=Pearce|first=Matt|date=August 23, 2013|accessdate=August 24, 2013|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfreporter.com/santafe/blog-4572-brian-egolf-to-court-compel-clerk-to-issue-same-sex-marriage-license.html|title=Brian Egolf to Court: Compel Clerk to Issue Same-Sex Marriage License|publisher=Sfreporter.com|date=June 6, 2013|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.documentcloud.org/documents/710121-sf-same-sex-marriage-petition.html#document/p1 ''Hanna and Hudson v. Salazar''], Docket No. D-101-CV-201302182, accessible here [https://caselookup.nmcourts.gov/caselookup/app].</ref> Although opponents filed for an [[injunction]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/aug/31/gop-lawmakers-bring-lawsuit-block-gay-marriage-lic/|work=The Washington Times|title=GOP lawmakers bring lawsuit to block gay marriage licenses in New Mexico|date=August 31, 2013|accessdate=August 31, 2013}}</ref> same-sex marriage expanded to a total of eight New Mexico counties.<ref>{{cite news|title=Judge OKs same-sex marriage in Bernalillo County|url=http://www.abqjournal.com/253280/news/clerk-prepares-samesex-licenses.html|newspaper=Albuquerque Journal News|last=Sanchez|first=Aurelio|date=August 26, 2013|accessdate=August 26, 2013}}</ref> On December 19, 2013, the state Supreme Court ruled unanimously that, effective immediately, same-sex marriage would be permitted throughout the state.<ref>{{cite news|last=Santos|first=Fernanda|title=New Mexico Becomes 17th State to Legalize Gay Marriage|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/20/us/new-mexico-becomes-17th-state-to-legalize-gay-marriage.html|accessdate=December 19, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=December 19, 2013}}</ref>

On December 20, 2013, Judge [[Robert J. Shelby]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Utah|U.S. District Court for Utah]] struck down [[Utah]]'s same-sex marriage ban as unconstitutional in ''[[Kitchen v. Herbert]].''<ref>{{cite news|title=Judge strikes down Utah’s same-sex marriage ban|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/judge-strikes-down-utahs-same-sex-marriage-ban/2013/12/20/f032442e-69bc-11e3-997b-9213b17dac97_story.html|accessdate=December 20, 2013|newspaper=Washington Post|date=December 20, 2013|deadurl=yes}} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> [[Salt Lake County, Utah|Salt Lake County]] began issuing marriage licenses immediately, followed by other counties.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marriage licenses being issued to gay couples in Utah|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865592784/Federal-judge-rules-Utahs-ban-on-same-sex-marriage-unconstitutional.html |accessdate=December 20, 2013|newspaper=Deseret News|date=December 20, 2013}}</ref> After failing to get the District Court or the Tenth Circuit Court of Appeals to stay the decision pending appeal, Utah state officials asked for a stay from the [[United States Supreme Court]], which granted the request on January 6, 2014.<ref name="Watkins, Tom" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2014/01/06/22201874-us-supreme-court-puts-gay-marriage-in-utah-on-hold?lite|title=U.S. Supreme Court puts gay marriage in Utah on hold|date=January 6, 2014|accessdate=January 6, 2014|author=Williams, Pete and Connor, Tracy}}</ref> The stay allowed Utah to reinstate its ban on same-sex marriage and deny state services to married same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite news|title=Utah won’t recognize same-sex marriages performed before stay|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/57367991-78/state-marriages-court-utah.html.csp|accessdate=January 8, 2014|newspaper=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=January 8, 2014|author=Brooke Adams|author2=Matthew Piper}}</ref> On January 10, U.S. Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] announced that the federal government would recognize the marriages of same-sex couples who married in Utah between December 20, 2013, and January 6, 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Geidner|first=Chris|title=Obama Administration To Recognize Utah Same-Sex Couples' Marriages |url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/obama-administration-to-recognize-utah-same-sex-couples-marr|accessdate=January 12, 2014|newspaper=Buzz Feed |date=January 10, 2014}}</ref> The Tenth Circuit ordered the appeals process to be heard on an expedited basis.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lang|first=Marissa |title=10th Circuit Court denies same-sex marriage stay|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/57306142-78/court-utah-state-sex.html.csp|accessdate=January 6, 2014|newspaper=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=December 24, 2013}}</ref>

===2014===

====January–May====
[[File:Recognition of same-sex unions in the United States.png|thumb|400px|Recognition of same-sex unions in the United States<sup>*</sup>
