<sup>*</sup>Rings indicate case-by-case approval, recognition for partial rights, local/tribal application, and "rogue"/civil disobedience jurisdictions. Rings also include previous cases of performance/recognition that have not been invalidated.  (Rings are placed in the center of each respective state).]]
On January 14, 2014, U.S. District Court Judge [[Terence C. Kern]] ruled in ''[[Bishop v. Oklahoma]]'' that Oklahoma's ban on same-sex marriage is unconstitutional. He stayed his ruling pending appeal.<ref name="chicagotribune1" /> On January 23, Virginia Attorney General [[Mark Herring]] announced that the state was reversing its position and supporting a federal lawsuit challenging the Virginia state constitution's ban on same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/blog/2014/02/04/Challenge-to-Virginias-same-sex-marriage-ban-reaches-federal-court/6741391537370/ |title=Judge promises to rule quickly on Virginia gay marriage ban |publisher=UPI.com |date=February 4, 2014| accessdate=February 13, 2014}}</ref> On January 21, a three-judge panel of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals]], considering issues unrelated to marriage in ''[[Batson challenge|SmithKline Beecham Corporation v. Abbott Laboratories]]'', ruled that distinctions based on sexual orientation are subject to the "heightened scrutiny" standard of review.<ref>{{cite news|last=Geidner |first=Chris |title=Federal Appeals Court Says Jurors Can't Be Excluded Because They Are Gay|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/federal-appeals-court-says-jurors-cant-be-excluded-because-t|accessdate=January 21, 2014|newspaper=Buzz Feed|date=January 21, 2014}}</ref> In response to that decision, on February 10, Nevada State Attorney General [[Catherine Cortez Masto]] withdrew the state's brief in ''[[Sevcik v. Sandoval]]'', ending its defense of the state's ban on same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gay Marriage Ban Support Slips in Nevada |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/11/us/gay-marriage-ban-support-slips-in-nevada.html|accessdate=February 13, 2014 |newspaper=New York Times|date=February 10, 2014}}</ref> Because the decision in ''SmithKline'' was not appealed, heightened scrutiny remains the standard of review in the Ninth Circuit for laws and government actions that draw distinctions based on sexual orientation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Geidner |first=Chris|title=Courts In 9 Western States To Review Anti-Gay Laws More Closely |url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/courts-in-9-western-states-to-review-anti-gay-laws-more-clos|accessdate=March 8, 2014 |publisher=BuzzFeed|date=March 8, 2014}}</ref>

On February 12, U.S. District Judge [[John G. Heyburn II|John G. Heyburn]] declared [[Same-sex marriage in Kentucky|Kentucky]]'s refusal to recognize same-sex marriages from other jurisdictions unconstitutional.<ref name="cheves1">{{cite web|last=Cheves |first=John |title=Federal judge: Kentucky must recognize same-sex marriages from other states|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2014/02/12/3083722/judge-ky-must-recognize-same-sex.html |accessdate=February 27, 2014 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=February 12, 2014}}</ref>{{r|KY district judge Feb 2014}} On February 27, Judge Heyburn issued an order requiring the state to recognize same-sex marriages performed in other jurisdictions,<ref>{{cite web|last=Barrouquere |first=Brett |url=http://news.yahoo.com/same-sex-marriage-now-legally-recognized-ky-190345106.html |title=Same-sex marriage now legally recognized in Ky |publisher=yahoo.com |accessdate=February 27, 2014}}</ref> but the next day he stayed that order until March 20.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wolfson |first=Andrew |title=Kentucky gay marriage ruling on hold until March 20|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/article/20140228/NEWS01/302280093/Kentucky-gay-marriage-ruling-hold-until-March-20 |accessdate=February 28, 2014|newspaper=Louisville Courier-Journal|date=February 28, 2014}}</ref> On March 19, the stay was extended pending action by the Sixth Circuit, noting the stay granted by the U.S. Supreme Court in ''[[Kitchen v. Herbert]]''.<ref name="Johnson">{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Chris|title=Judge stays order requiring Ky. to recognize same-sex marriages |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/03/19/judge-stays-order-requiring-kentucky-recognize-gay-marriages/|accessdate=March 20, 2014|newspaper=Washington Blade|date=March 19, 2014}}</ref> Additionally, on July 1, a judge ruled in&nbsp;Love v. Beshear that the ban on performing same-sex marriage within Kentucky was unconstitutional, and also stayed the ruling.<ref>{{cite web|first=Andrew |last=Wolfson |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/local/2014/07/01/gays-right-marry-kentucky-judge-rules/11900313/ |title=Federal judge in Louisville rules gays have right to marry in Kentucky |publisher=Courier-journal.com |date=July 2, 2014 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref>

On February 13, Judge [[Arenda L. Wright Allen]] of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia|U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia]] ruled that the state's ban on same-sex marriage is unconstitutional. She stayed enforcement of her ruling in ''[[Bostic v. Rainey]]'' pending appeal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Federal-Judge-Rules-Va-Gay-Marriage-Ban-Unconstitutional-245473531.html |title=Federal Judge Rules Va. Gay Marriage Ban Unconstitutional |publisher=nbcwashington.com |date=February 13, 2014 |accessdate=February 13, 2014}}</ref>

On February 26, U.S. District Judge [[Orlando Luis Garcia|Orlando Garcia]] ruled in ''[[Same-sex marriage in Texas#De Leon v. Perry|De Leon v. Perry]]'' that Texas's ban on same-sex marriage is an unconstitutional "state-imposed inequality".<ref>{{cite web|last=Fahrenthold |first=David A. |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/judge-strikes-down-texas-gay-marriage-ban-paving-way-for-shift-in-conservative-bastion/2014/02/26/201d6cd0-9f1f-11e3-9ba6-800d1192d08b_story.html |title=Judge strikes down Tex. same-sex marriage ban, paving way for shift in conservative state |publisher=The Washington Post |date=February 28, 2011 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> He immediately stayed the effect of his ruling, pending an appeal. Texas Attorney General [[Greg Abbott]] said that he would appeal the ruling to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit|Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Garrett|first=Robert |title=Federal judge voids Texas' gay marriage ban, though he delays order from taking effect immediately |url=http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/2014/02/federal-judge-voids-texas-gay-marriage-ban-though-he-delays-order-from-taking-effect-immediately.html/ |accessdate=February 26, 2014|newspaper=Dallas News|date=February 26, 2014}}</ref>

On March 4, Illinois Attorney General [[Lisa Madigan]] issued an opinion that a recent court decision ordering Cook County to issue marriage licenses immediately did not apply to all county clerks, but advised clerks that they should find the decision "persuasive as you evaluate whether to issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples." Governor [[Pat Quinn (politician)|Pat Quinn]] then announced that the [[Illinois Department of Public Health]] would record marriages issued by any county clerk.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merevick|first1=Tony |last2=Geidner |first2=Chris|title=Illinois Attorney General Hedges On Marriage Equality Question|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/tonymerevick/illinois-attorney-general-hedges-on-marriage-equality-questi |accessdate=March 5, 2014|publisher=BuzzFeed |date=March 4, 2014}}</ref> Several of the state's [[List of counties in Illinois|102 county clerks]] began, or announced plans to begin, issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples in March.<ref>{{cite news|title=More Illinois counties to issue gay-marriage licenses|url=http://thesouthern.com/news/local/more-illinois-counties-to-issue-gay-marriage-licenses/article_ae09c624-6c53-55e9-adb8-caf2be28338d.html|accessdate=March 9, 2014 |newspaper=The Southern Illinoian|date=March 7, 2014}}</ref>

On March 21, U.S. District Court Judge [[Bernard A. Friedman]] found Michigan's ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional. He did not stay enforcement of his decision. Michigan Attorney General [[Bill Schuette]] filed an emergency request with the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals]] for a stay pending appeal.<ref>{{cite news|last=Snow|first=Justin|title=Federal court strikes down Michigan's same-sex marriage ban|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/poliglot/2014/03/federal-court-strikes-down-michigans-same-sex-marr.html|accessdate=March 21, 2014|newspaper=Metro Weekly|date=March 21, 2014}}</ref> Hundreds of same-sex couples obtained marriage licenses and some married in Michigan on the morning of March 22 before the appeals court temporarily stayed enforcement of the ruling until March 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/detroit/index.ssf/2014/03/gay_couples_wed_across_michiga.html|title=Gay couples wed across Michigan in 24 hours same-sex marriage was legal|work=Michigan Live|date=March 22, 2014|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> On March 25, the stay pending appeal was granted by the appellate court.

On May 9, 2014, Pulaski County Circuit Judge Chris Piazza struck down Arkansas' constitutional ban on same-sex marriage in ''[[Wright v. Arkansas]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2014/05/arkansas-judge-strikes-down-same-sex-marriage-ban/ |title=Arkansas judge strikes down same-sex marriage ban}}</ref> As the details of his ruling and requests for a stay were considered, approximately 450 same-sex marriage licenses were issued. The [[Arkansas Supreme Court]] stayed enforcement of his ruling pending appeal on May 16.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://time.com/103572/arkansas-gay-marriage-suspension-ruling/ | title=Gay marriage on hold in Arkansas following new ruling | work=Time | date = May 16, 2014 | accessdate=May 17, 2014}}</ref>

On May 13, U.S. District Magistrate Judge Candy Dale in ''[[Latta v. Otter]]'' issued a ruling striking down Idaho's ban on marriage for same-sex couples. She ordered the state to allow same-sex couples to marry and to recognize same-sex marriages from other jurisdictions.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Somin|first1=Ilya|title=Federal judge strikes down Idaho law banning same-sex marriage|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/volokh-conspiracy/wp/2014/05/14/federal-judge-strikes-down-idaho-law-banning-same-sex-marriage/|accessdate=October 1, 2014|work=Washington Post|date=May 14, 2014}}</ref> On May 20, a three-judge panel of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals]] issued a stay pending appeal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=La Ganga|first1=Maria L.|title=Appeals court says same-sex marriages will stay on hold in Idaho |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-idaho-same-sex-marriages-on-hold-20140520-story.html |accessdate=October 1, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 20, 2014}}</ref>

On May 19, U.S. District judge [[Michael J. McShane]] ruled in ''[[Geiger v. Kitzhaber]]'' that Oregon's same-sex marriage ban was unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news|last=KGW Staff|title=Gay couples getting married after Oregon ban overturned |url=http://www.kgw.com/news/Oregon-gay-couples-line-up-for-potential-marriage-licenses-259815911.html|date=May 19, 2014}}</ref> Judge McShane ordered marriages to begin immediately.<ref name="Mapes">{{cite news|last=Mapes|first=Jeff |title=Ninth Circuit strikes down National Organization's request to halt judge's decision|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/mapes/index.ssf/2014/05/gay_marriage_in_oregon_ninth_c.html|date=May 19, 2014}}</ref> The [[National Organization for Marriage]] filed a petition to intervene as defendants in the case, two days before oral arguments; the petition was denied. Both the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals and the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] denied NOM's emergency request for a stay on Judge McShane's ruling, thereby permanently legalizing same-sex marriage in the state.<ref name="Mapes" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Supreme Court Rebuffs Call to End Same-Sex Marriages in Oregon|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/05/us/politics/supreme-court-rebuffs-call-to-end-same-sex-marriages-in-oregon.html?emc=edit_tnt_20140604&nlid=56632514&tntemail0=y|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nat'l Organization for Marriage V. Geiger, Deanna L., et al.|url=http://media.oregonlive.com/mapes/other/13A1173%20NOM%20v%20%20Geiger%20Order.pdf|publisher=Supreme Court of the United States|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref>

On May 20, 2014, Judge John E. Jones III of the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of Pennsylvania]] struck down Pennsylvania's same-sex marriage ban in his ruling in ''[[Whitewood v. Wolf]]''.<ref name="Buzzfeed">{{cite news|last=Buzzfeed|title=Federal Judge Strikes Down Pennsylvania Same-Sex Marriage Ban|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/federal-judge-strikes-down-pennsylvania-same-sex-marriage-ba|accessdate=May 20, 2014|date=May 20, 2014}}</ref> Governor [[Tom Corbett]] said he will not appeal the court decision, effectively legalizing same-sex marriage in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web|author=Marc Levy |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/21/tom-corbett-gay-marriage_n_5367313.html |title=Pennsylvania Governor Won't Appeal Ruling Striking Down Gay Marriage Ban |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=May 21, 2014 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> One county clerk has decided to intervene in, appeal, and stay the decision. The trial court denied intervention and the stay of judgment, and the Third Circuit affirmed. On July 7, 2014, the clerk applied to the U.S. Supreme Court for a stay. U.S. Supreme Court [[Associate Justice]] [[Samuel Alito]], [[Circuit justice|Circuit Justice]] for the Third Circuit, denied the clerk's application for a stay on July 8, 2014, and the Third Circuit denied the clerk's petition to rehear her case for intervention on August 4, 2014.<ref name="LBGTQ Nation.com">{{cite news|author=Associated Press|title=Justice Alito denies clerk’s bid to halt same-sex marriage in Pennsylvania|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2014/07/justice-alito-denies-clerks-bid-to-halt-same-sex-marriage-in-pennsylvania/|publisher=LBGTQ Nation.com|date=July 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceC">{{cite news|author=Patty Shwartz, Circuit Judge|title=''Sur'' Petition for Rehearing ''Whitewood v. Secretary Pa. Dep't of Health'', No. 14-3048|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/assets/2014/08/Third-Circuit-Santai-Gaffney-en-banc-denial.pdf|publisher=[[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]|agency=Scribd.com|publisher=[[PACER (law)|PACER]] Document 3111697838|date=August 4, 2014}}</ref>

====June–September====
On June 6, 2014, Judge Barbara Bandriff Crabb of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Wisconsin]] struck down Wisconsin's same-sex marriage ban in ''[[Wolf v. Walker]]''.<ref>[http://lawprofessors.typepad.com/files/wolfvwalker.pdf Wolf v. Walker], 14-cv-64-bbc, (W.D. Michigan June 6, 2014) p 3</ref> No immediate injunction to stop enforcement of the ban was ordered,<ref name="Sentinel">{{cite news|author1=Jason Stein|author2=Patrick Marley|author3=Dana Ferguson|title=Federal judge overturns Wisconsin's gay marriage ban|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/statepolitics/federal-judge-overturns-wisconsins-gay-marriage-ban-b99286138z1-262161851.html|accessdate=Jun 6, 2014|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=June 6, 2014}}</ref> and county clerks in at least 60 counties have begun to issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2014/06/all-but-nine-wis-counties-now-issuing-marriage-licenses-to-same-sex-couples/ |title=All but twelve Wis. counties now issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples |publisher=Lgbtqnation.com |date=June 12, 2014 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> After Judge Barbara Crabb refused to stay her ruling, Wisconsin's attorney general [[J. B. Van Hollen]] requested a stay from the [[Same-sex marriage in the Seventh Circuit|Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals]] in Chicago. On June 13, the judge put the ruling on hold, pending appeal.<ref name="ReferenceB">{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2014/06/federal-judge-put-same-sex-marriages-in-wisconsin-on-hold-pending-appeal/ |title=Federal judge puts same-sex marriages in Wisconsin on hold pending appeal |publisher=Lgbtqnation.com |date=June 6, 2014 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref>

On June 25, 2014, the [[Same-sex marriage in the Tenth Circuit|Tenth Circuit]] Court affirmed Judge Robert Shelby's ruling striking Utah's same-sex marriage ban.<ref>{{cite news|last=Miller, Stewart and Manson|first=|title=10th Circuit Court upholds same-sex marriage in Utah|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/58007681-78/court-marriage-appeals-sex.html.csp |accessdate=July 19, 2014|newspaper=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref><ref name="SLT20140625">{{cite news |author1=Jessica Miller, Kirsten Stewart and Pamela Manson|title=10th Circuit Court upholds same-sex marriage |url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/58007681-78/court-marriage-appeals-sex.html.csp|accessdate=July 12, 2014|publisher=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=25 June 2014}}</ref> It was the first time a federal appeals court recognized that same-sex couples have a fundamental right to marry.<ref name="SLT20140625" /> The judgment was stayed pending review from the Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nearly simultaneous decisions strike down gay marriage bans|url=http://www.cnycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=1062365#.U6svVSjA1cg|accessdate=Jun 25, 2014|work=CNYCentral|agency=The Associated Press|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Canham|first1=Matt|title=Answering your questions on the same-sex marriage ruling|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/58113585-78/court-marriage-state-ruling.html.csp|accessdate=Jun 25, 2014|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref> Boulder County in Colorado, a state in the Tenth Circuit's jurisdiction, began issuing licenses despite the stay until ordered by the [[Colorado Supreme Court]] to stop. The same day, a federal district court in [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Indiana|Indiana]] ruled [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Indiana|Indiana]]'s ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional. Judge [[Richard L. Young]] did not issue a stay on his ruling and instructed all state agencies to provide marital benefits to same-sex couples.{{r|insd.uscourts June 25, 2014}} Two days later, the order was stayed by the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals]] pending appeal.{{r|7th Circuit stay June 27, 2014}}

On July 9, 2014, a state judge struck down Colorado's same-sex marriage ban in ''[[Same-sex marriage in Colorado#Brinkman v. Long|Brinkman v. Long]]'', staying the decision pending appeal.<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomaston|first=Scottie|title=Colorado same-sex marriage ban ruled unconstitutional|url=http://equalityontrial.com/2014/07/09/colorado-sex-marriage-ban-ruled-unconstitutional/|work=Equality On Trial|date=July 9, 2014}}</ref> A number of county clerks issued marriage licenses to same-sex couples on July 29, 2014, before an order from the [[Colorado Supreme Court]] halted the practice a month after a handful of county clerks had defied a ban in the State Constitution.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Healy|first1=Jack|title=Colorado Clerk Told to Stop Issuing Marriage Licenses to Gay Couples |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/30/us/colorado-clerk-told-to-stop-issuing-gay-marriage-licenses.html |accessdate=September 29, 2014|work=New York Times|date=July 29, 2014}}</ref> On July 23, in ''[[Burns v. Hickenlooper]]'', U.S. District Judge [[Raymond P. Moore]] also ruled that Colorado's ban against same-sex marriage is unconstitutional. On August 21, the Tenth Circuit Court of Appeals stayed the enforcement of ''Burns'' pending action by  the U.S. Supreme Court on petitions for [[certiorari]] in similar cases.

In July and August 2014, several state judges in Florida found the state constitution's ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional; all their orders were stayed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/07/17/gay-same-sex-marriage-florida-keys/12786169/ |title=Ruling allows same-sex marriages for Florida Keys |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=July 17, 2014 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Rothaus |first=Steve |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article1977113.html |title=Miami-Dade judge: Florida's gay-marriage ban unconstitutional; couples can wed, but not until case is appealed |work=Miami Herald |date=July 25, 2014 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref>  On August 21, 2014, U.S. District Judge Robert Hinkle made a similar ruling and stayed enforcement pending further appeals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/08/21/us-federal-judge-rules-floridas-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional/ |title=US: Federal judge rules Florida's same-sex marriage ban unconstitutional |publisher=Pinknews.co.uk |date=August 21, 2014 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> On July 28, 2014, the Fourth Circuit affirmed the unconstitutionality of Virginia's ban on same-sex marriage in ''[[Bostic v. Schaefer]]''.<ref name="washingtonpost.com">{{cite web|last=Carpenter |first=Dale |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/volokh-conspiracy/wp/2014/07/28/fourth-circuit-strikes-down-virginia-ban-on-same-sex-marriage/ |title=Fourth Circuit strikes down Virginia ban on same-sex marriage |publisher=The Washington Post |date=July 28, 2014 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> The U.S. Supreme Court issued a stay on August 20, 2014, one day before the Fourth Circuit's mandate was to go into effect. On September 4, 2014, a three-judge panel of the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals unanimously affirmed the unconstitutionality of Indiana and Wisconsin's bans on same-sex marriage in ''[[Baskin v. Bogan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eckholm|first1=Eric |title=Gay-Marriage Bans Fall In Wisconsin and Indiana|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/05/us/us-appellate-court-overturns-same-sex-marriage-bans-in-wisconsin-and-indiana.html|work=New York Times|date=September 4, 2014|accessdate=September 29, 2014}}</ref> The Court stayed its decision before it took effect, pending action by U.S. Supreme Court.<ref name=wolfstay>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Jason |title=Wisconsin's gay marriage ban to stay in place until U.S. Supreme Court rules |url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/statepolitics/gay-marriage-ban-to-stay-in-place-until-us-supreme-court-rules-b99353767z1-275484751.html |accessdate=September 18, 2014|work=Milwaukee Wisconsin Journal-Sentinel|date=September 18, 2014}}</ref>

On September 3, District Judge [[Martin Leach-Cross Feldman|Martin Feldman]] ruled against the plaintiff same-sex couples in ''[[Robicheaux v. Caldwell]]'', upholding Louisiana's ban on same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robertson |first1=Campbell |title=Federal Judge, Bucking Trend, Affirms Ban on Same-Sex Marriages in Louisiana |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/us/louisiana-gay-marriage-ban-upheld-by-federal-judge.html|accessdate=September 20, 2014|work=New York Times|date=September 3, 2014}}</ref>

====October====
On October 6, 2014, the U.S. Supreme Court declined to take action on all five cases it had been asked to consider from appellate courts in the Fourth, Seventh, and Tenth Circuits, allowing the circuit court decisions striking down marriage bans to stand.<ref name=scotusdecline>{{cite web| url=http://www.cnbc.com/id/102058024 |title=US Supreme Court declines to intervene in gay marriage cases |publisher=cnbc.com |date=October 6, 2014 |accessdate=October 6, 2014}}</ref> The Tenth Circuit, lifting its stays in two cases that same day, ordered Oklahoma and Utah to recognize same-sex marriage, as did the Fourth Circuit for Virginia.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Portnoy|first1=Jenna|title=Same-sex marriages in Virginia can begin immediately|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/same-sex-marriages-in-virginia-can-begin-almost-immediately/2014/10/06/97ceab2e-4d69-11e4-aa5e-7153e466a02d_story.html|accessdate=October 6, 2014|work=Washington Post |date=October 6, 2014}}</ref> The stays in the Seventh Circuit's cases expired automatically with the Supreme Court's dismissal of the certiorari petitions, allowing its rulings that Indiana and Wisconsin must recognize same-sex marriage to take effect.<ref>{{cite web|title=Order, ''Baskin v. Bogan'', September 15, 2014|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/239799373/14-2386-217 |publisher=Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals|accessdate=October 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein |first1=Jason |title=Wisconsin's gay marriage ban to stay in place until U.S. Supreme Court rules|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/statepolitics/gay-marriage-ban-to-stay-in-place-until-us-supreme-court-rules-b99353767z1-275484751.html |accessdate=October 6, 2014|work=Milwaukee Wisconsin Journal-Sentinel|date=September 18, 2014}}</ref> Same-sex marriage bans were expected to end in the six other states in those circuits that still banned same-sex marriage<ref>{{cite news|last1=Denniston|first1=Lyle|title=Many more same-sex marriages soon, but where?|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2014/10/many-more-same-sex-marriages-soon-but-where/|accessdate=October 7, 2014|work=SCOTUSblog|date=October 6, 2014}}</ref>–Colorado, Kansas, North Carolina, South Carolina, West Virginia, and Wyoming–as courts implemented the rulings in their circuits, but officials in South Carolina, Wyoming, and Kansas said they would continue to defend their states' bans.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chappell|first1=Bill|title=In Gay Marriage's New Landscape, Glee, Confusion And Resistance|url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/10/07/354304166/in-gay-marriage-s-new-landscape-glee-confusion-and-resistance |accessdate=October 7, 2014|work=NPR|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> Colorado Attorney General John Suthers, by contrast, asked the Tenth Circuit to dismiss his appeal and lift its stay in ''Burns v. Hickenlooper''. He asked the State Supreme Court to lift a stay preventing certain clerks from issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples. Both courts lifted their stays on October 7, 2014, and Suthers ordered all county clerks to issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Steffen |first1=Jordan |title=Colorado Supreme Court, Suthers clear way for same-sex licenses|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_26679238/colorado-supreme-court-clears-county-clerks-issue-same|accessdate=October 7, 2014|work=Denver Post|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> As of October 6, 2014, most Americans live in a state that recognizes same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bump|first1=Philip|title=A majority of gay Americans now live in states where gay marriage is legal|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/10/07/a-majority-of-gay-americans-now-live-in-states-where-gay-marriage-is-legal/|accessdate=9 October 2014|work=The Washington Post|date=7 October 2014}}</ref>

On October 7, 2014, the Ninth Circuit ruled in two cases, overturning a district court in Nevada that had found that state's ban on same-sex marriage constitutional and affirming the decision of a district court in Idaho that had found that state's ban unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Geidner|first1=Chris|title=Idaho And Nevada Marriage Bans Are Unconstitutional, Federal Appeals Court Rules|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/idaho-and-nevado-marriage-bans-are-unconstitutional-federal#3qn1tx0|accessdate=October 7, 2014|work=BuzzFeed News|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> In the case of Idaho, it issued the lower court's order requiring Idaho to cease enforcing its ban on same-sex marriage immediately.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berry|first1=Harrison|title=9th Circuit Declares Idaho Same-Sex Couples May Marry Immediately|url=http://www.boiseweekly.com/CityDesk/archives/2014/10/07/ada-county-isnt-processing-same-sex-marriage-licenses-just-yetits-up-to-judge-candy-dale-again|accessdate=October 7, 2014|work=Boise Weekly|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> In the case of Nevada, the Ninth Circuit said it was ordering the district court in Nevada to issue a similar order with respect to that state.<ref>{{cite web|title=Opinion, October 7, 2014|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/242214412/9th-Circuit-Idaho-Nevada-Same-Sex-Marriage-Ruling|website=Scribd.com|publisher=Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref> In a joint statement, Nevada's Governor Brian Sandoval and Attorney General Catherine Cortez Masto said the state would not appeal the decision. It said: "Same sex marriage is now law in Nevada".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ritter|first1=Ken|title=Marriage bureau in Vegas preps for gay marriages|url=https://www.ksl.com/?nid=157&sid=31866540&title=marriage-bureau-in-vegas-preps-for-gay-marriages|accessdate=October 8, 2014|work=KSL TV|agency=Associated Press|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref>

On October 8, 2014, Idaho officials asked that the Ninth Circuit allow enforcement of Idaho's same-sex marriage ban to continue while they sought rehearing ''en banc.'' They also asked the U.S. Supreme Court to stay implementation of the Ninth Circuit's decision while they sought rehearing by the Ninth Circuit or consideration by the Supreme Court. They cited a [[circuit split]] on the question of whether government actions that make distinctions on the basis of sexual orientation require review under the "[[heightened scrutiny]]" standard, to which few circuits have adopted.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Denniston |first1=Lyle|title=Idaho same-sex marriages delayed|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2014/10/idaho-asks-same-sex-marriage-delay/|accessdate=October 8, 2014|work=SCOTUSblog|date=October 8, 2014}}</ref> Justice Anthony Kennedy granted an emergency stay,<ref name="news.yahoo.com">{{cite news|title=U.S. justice temporarily blocks Idaho gay marriage ruling |url=http://news.yahoo.com/u-justice-temporarily-blocks-idaho-gay-marriage-ruling-135953780.html|accessdate=October 8, 2014 |agency=Reuters|date=October 8, 2014}}</ref> which he withdrew when the full Supreme Court denied the stay request.<ref>{{cite news|title=Supreme Court Lifts Stay on Same-Sex Marriages in Idaho|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/11/us/politics/supreme-court-lifts-stay-on-same-sex-marriages-in-idaho.html|accessdate=October 10, 2014|work=New York Times|date = October 10, 2014}}</ref> Idaho Governor [[Butch Otter]] announced the state would no longer attempt to preserve the state's denial of marriage rights to same-sex couples,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sewell|first1=Cynthia|title=Otter says state should comply with gay-marriage order when it comes again |url=http://www.idahostatesman.com/2014/10/10/3420813_what-is-the-status-of-idahos-gay.html |accessdate=October 10, 2014 |work=Idaho Statesman|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> but Idaho sought another stay from the Ninth Circuit, which rejected the request on October 15.<ref>{{cite web|title=Order Re: Denial of Stay |url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/general/2014/10/15/14-35420%2010-15%20Opinion%20and%20Order.pdf |publisher=United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref>

Also on October 8, 2014, the chief judge of the state district court for [[Johnson County, Kansas|Johnson County]], Kansas, the most populous in the state, directed the court's clerk to issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite news |title=Johnson County chief judge gives green light to gay marriage in Kansas|url=http://www2.ljworld.com/news/2014/oct/08/johnson-county-chief-judge-gives-green-light-gay-m/|accessdate=October 8, 2014|work=Lawrence Journal-World|date=October 8, 2014}}</ref> On October 10, Kansas Chief Justice [[Lawton Nuss]] ordered all court clerks not to issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples, but allowed the acceptance of applications for marriage licenses to continue.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kansas AG seeks to halt same-sex marriages in his state |first=Chris |last=Johnson|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/10/10/kansas-ag-seeks-halt-sex-marriages-state/ |work=Washington Blade|date=October 10, 2014|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> Also on October 8, 2014, in South Carolina, some same-sex couples obtained marriage licenses,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith |first1=Bruce|title=Gay marriages start in SC|url=http://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/2014/10/08/gay-marriages-start-sc/16911323/|accessdate=October 8, 2014 |work=Citizen-Times|agency=Associated Press|date=October 8, 2014}}</ref> but the South Carolina Supreme Court ordered a halt to their issuance the next day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Collins |first1=Jeffrey|title=South Carolina Supreme Court Halts Same-Sex Marriage Licenses |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/10/09/same-sex-marriage-south-carolina_n_5959642.html |accessdate=October 9, 2014|work=Huffington Post|agency=Associated Press |date=October 9, 2014}}</ref>

On October 9, West Virginia Governor [[Earl Ray Tomblin|Ray Tomblin]] announced he was ordering state agencies to act in compliance with the recent decisions of federal courts on the unconstitutionality of same-sex marriage bans.<ref>{{cite news|title=Governor Tomblin Issues Statement Regarding Same-Sex Marriage in West Virginia|url=http://www.governor.wv.gov/media/pressreleases/2014/Pages/GOVERNOR-TOMBLIN-ISSUES-STATEMENT-REGARDING-SAME-SEX-MARRIAGE-IN-WEST-VIRGINIA.aspx |accessdate=October 9, 2014|publisher=Office of the Governor|date=October 9, 2014}}</ref> On October 10, District Court Judge [[Max O. Cogburn, Jr.]], ruling in ''General Synod of the United Church of Christ v. Cooper'', struck down North Carolina's ban on same-sex marriage, citing the Fourth Circuit's ruling in ''Bostic v. Schaefer''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Snow |first1=Justin |title=Federal judge strikes down North Carolina same-sex marriage ban|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/10/federal-judge-strikes-down-north-carolina-same-sex-marriage-ban/|accessdate=October 10, 2014|work=Metro Weekly|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> Some North Carolina clerks began issuing marriage license to same-sex couple immediately.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Price|first1=Mark|title=Mecklenburg marriage licenses start Monday; some cities started Friday |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2014/10/10/5234182/mecklenburg-marriage-licenses.html#.VDij5le1uSo |accessdate=October 10, 2014|work=Charlotte Observer|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> The ban in West Virginia was officially declared unconstitutional on November 7, 2014, by U.S. District Judge [[Robert C. Chambers]].<ref name="Herald-Dispatch"/>

The ACLU filed a lawsuit, ''Marie v. Moser'', in U.S. district court in Kansas on October 10 on behalf of two lesbian couples who had been refused marriage licenses in the last few days. The suit named as defendants Robert Moser, Secretary of the Kansas Department of Health and Environment, and two district court clerks.<ref name="Complaint, October 10, 2014">{{cite web|title=Complaint, October 10, 2014|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/242720672/2-14-cv-02518-1-Complaint|website=Scribd.com|publisher=U.S. District Court for Kansas|accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref>

On October 12, 2014, Judge [[Timothy Burgess|Timothy M. Burgess]] ruled that Alaska's denial of marriage rights to same-sex couples is unconstitutional and issued an injunction to prevent state officials from continuing to enforce it.<ref name=NYTalaska /> Alaska Governor [[Sean Parnell]] immediately stated his intention to appeal the decision, and the head of the state Bureau of Vital Statistics said, "We expect our office will be busy tomorrow, (October 13) but we will make every effort to help customers as quickly as possible."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boots |first1=Michelle Theriault|title=State vows to appeal after Alaska's same-sex marriage ban struck down |url=http://www.adn.com/article/20141012/alaskas-same-sex-marriage-ban-ruled-unconstitutional-state-will-appeal|work=Alaska Dispatch News|accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref>

On October 13, 2014, the Ninth Circuit lifted the stay it had imposed on May 20, 2014, in ''[[Latta v. Otter]]'', allowing the district court decision to take effect, preventing further enforcement of Idaho's ban on same-sex marriage as of October 15, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=First Ada County licenses issued to two plaintiff couples from Idaho’s same-sex marriage case|url=http://www.spokesman.com/blogs/boise/2014/oct/15/first-ada-county-licenses-issued-two-plaintiff-couples-idahos-same-sex-marriage-case/|accessdate=October 15, 2014|work=Spokesman Review|date=October 15, 2014}}</ref> Also on October 13, the Coalition for the Protection of Marriage asked the Ninth Circuit to rehear ''Sevcik'' ''en banc,'' charging that the Ninth Circuit's assignment of judges to cases that raise LGBT rights issues "did not result from a neutral judge-assignment process."<ref>{{cite news|work=BuzzFeed News| accessdate=October 13, 2014|date=October 13, 2014|title=Lawyer: It Looks Like Court Assigned Marriage Cases To Specific Judges "To Influence The Outcome"|first=Chris |last=Geidner| url= http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/lawyer-it-looks-like-court-assigned-marriage-cases-to-specif }}</ref>

On October 17, 2014, U.S. District Judge John W. Sedwick declared Arizona's ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional and enjoined the state from enforcing its ban, effective immediately. Arizona Attorney General [[Tom Horne]] said the state would not appeal the ruling and instructed county clerks to issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Westfall |first1=Julie|last2=Queally|first2=James|title=Arizona's gay marriage ban struck down, AG will not appeal|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-arizonas-gay-marriage-ban-struck-down-20141017-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=October 17, 2014|date=October 17, 2014}}</ref> On the same day, U.S. District Judge [[Scott Skavdahl]] ruled for the plaintiff same-sex couples in Wyoming in ''[[Same-sex marriage in Wyoming|Guzzo v. Mead]]'', but stayed enforcement of his ruling until October 23 or until the defendants informed the court that they will not appeal to the Tenth Circuit. The stay was lifted on October 21 when the state notified the court it would not appeal, ending enforcement of Wyoming's ban on same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moern|first1=Bob|title=Wyoming Legalizes Same-Sex Marriage |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/wyoming-prepares-legalize-sex-marriage-26342611|accessdate=October 21, 2014|work=ABC News|agency=Associated Press|date=October 21, 2014}}</ref>

====November–present====
On November 4, 2014, U.S. District Judge [[Daniel D. Crabtree]] ruled in ''[[Marie v. Moser]]'' that Kansas' ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional and stayed enforcement of his ruling against state officials until 5 pm CST on November 11 unless the state defendants inform the court before then that they will not appeal the decision.<ref name=kansas>{{cite news|last1=Snow|first1=Justin |title=Federal judge rules against Kansas same-sex marriage ban|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/11/federal-judge-rules-against-kansas-same-sex-marriage-ban/|accessdate=November 4, 2014|work=Metro Weekly|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Order granting preliminary injunction|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/245530706/2-14-cv-02518-29-ORDER |website=Scribd.com |publisher=U.S. District Court for Kansas|accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref> Kansas Attorney General [[Derek Schmidt]] announced the state planned to appeal and seek an initial hearing ''en banc'' from the Tenth Circuit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|title=Judge rules against Kansas same-sex marriage ban |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/11/04/judge-rules-kansas-sex-marriage-ban/|accessdate=November 4, 2014 |work=Washington Blade|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref> He sought a temporary stay from the Tenth Circuit without success and then asked Supreme Court Justice [[Sonia Sotomayor]], as Circuit Justice for the Tenth Circuit, to issue a stay pending appeal. On November 10 she granted a temporary stay pending consideration of their request. She referred the matter to the full court, which on November 12, with Justices [[Antonin Scalia]] and [[Clarence Thomas]] dissenting, declined to issue a stay and lifted Sotomayor's temporary stay, leaving Judge Crabtree's order against the enforcement of Kansas' ban on same-sex marriage in place.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stohr|first1=Greg|title=U.S. Supreme Court Clears Gay Marriage to Start in Kansas|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-11-12/u-s-supreme-court-clears-gay-marriage-to-start-in-kansas.html |accessdate=November 12, 2014|work=Bloomberg News|date=November 12, 2014}}</ref>

On November 5, 2014, a state judge in St. Louis ruled Missouri's ban unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Zagier |first1=Alan Scher|title=Missouri Gay Marriage Ban Ruled Unconstitutional|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/11/05/missouri-gay-marriage_n_6110348.html|accessdate=November 6, 2014 |work=Huffington Post|date=November 5, 2014}}</ref> Missouri Attorney General Chris Koster announced plans to appeal the ruling to the Missouri Supreme Court, but not to seek a stay of the ruling's implementation because "[f]ollowing decisions in Idaho and Alaska, the United States Supreme Court has refused to grant stays on identical facts."<ref>{{cite news|title=AG Koster's statement regarding today's ruling in St. Louis same-sex marriage case|url=http://ago.mo.gov/newsreleases/2014/AG_Koster_ruling_StLouis_same-sex_marriage/ |accessdate=November 5, 2014|publisher=Missouri Attorney General|date=November 5, 2014}}</ref> The ruling directed [[St. Louis]] to issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples and the city's marriage license department immediately complied.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moore|first=Doug|title=Judge rules that gay marriage ban in Missouri is unconstitutional |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/judge-rules-that-gay-marriage-ban-in-missouri-is-unconstitutional/article_f9e3bd74-d9bf-5337-ba22-88cd5614e59d.html |accessdate=November 6, 2014|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|date=November 6, 2014}}</ref> [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]], where an official said "We believe it's a county-by-county decision",<ref name=lieb>{{cite news|last1=Lieb|first1=David A.|title=Many Missouri Counties Not Granting Gay Marriages |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/missouri-counties-granting-gay-marriages-26736974|accessdate=November 7, 2014|work=ABC News|agency=Associated Press|date=November 6, 2014}}</ref> began issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples the next day.<ref>{{cite news|title=St. Louis County Complies with Ruling on Gay Marriage Ban, Issues First Two Same Sex Marriage Licenses |url=http://www.stlouisco.com/Community/News/Article/925/St-Louis-County-Complies-with-Ruling-on-Gay-Marriage-Ban-Issues-First-Two-Same|accessdate=November 6, 2014|publisher=St. Louis County|date=November 6, 2014}}</ref> Koster and the Recorders' Association of Missouri said the decision only applied to the city of St. Louis.<ref name=lieb/>

On November 6, 2014, the [[Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]], in a 2-1 decision, upheld the same-sex marriage bans in Kentucky, Michigan, Ohio, and Tennessee.<ref name="Thomaston"/> Attorneys for the plaintiffs in all six of the cases planned to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court rather than ask the Sixth Circuit to rehear the case ''en banc''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dennison|first1=Lyle|title=Analysis: Paths to same-sex marriage review |url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2014/11/analysis-paths-to-same-sex-marriage-review/|accessdate=November 7, 2014|work=SCOTUSblog|date=November 7, 2014}}</ref>

On November 7, a U.S. District Court judge ruled in ''[[LGBT rights in Missouri|Lawson v. Jackson County]]'' that Missouri's ban on same-sex marriage was unconstitutional. He stayed enforcement of his ruling pending appeal, and the Attorney General announced plans to appeal to the [[Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals|Eighth Circuit]].<ref>{{cite news|work=BuzzFeed News|first=Chris |last=Geidner |date=November 7, 2014 |accessdate=November 7, 2014|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/missouris-same-sex-marriage-ban-is-unconstitutional-federal| title=Missouri’s Same-Sex Marriage Ban Is Unconstitutional, Federal Judge Rules}}</ref> In [[Jackson County, Missouri|Jackson County]], which includes [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]], officials began issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples the same day.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morris|first1=Mark|title=Judge calls Missouri same-sex marriage ban unconstitutional, Jackson County to issue licenses|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/government-politics/article3619714.html |accessdate=November 7, 2014|work=Kansas City Star|date=November 7, 2014}}</ref>

On November 12, U.S. District Court Judge [[Richard Gergel]] ruled South Carolina's ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional in ''[[Condon v. Haley]]''. He issued a temporary stay of his ruling until noon on November 20.<ref name=SCstrike/>

Several of Kansas's 105 counties began issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples for the first time on November 13, though the state attorney general contended that the federal court order in ''Marie v. Moser'' only applied to two counties. The [[Kansas Supreme Court]]'s temporary order in ''State v. Moriarty'' that one judicial district not issue such licenses remained in place,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe|first1=Peggy |last2=Margolies|first2=Dan|title=Some Kansas Counties Issue Marriage Licenses to Gay Couples |url=http://kcur.org/post/some-kansas-counties-issue-marriage-licenses-gay-couples |accessdate=November 13, 2014 |publisher=KCUR |date=November 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Order, ''State v. Moriarty'', October 10, 2014|url=http://www.kscourts.org/State_v_Moriarty/112590.pdf|publisher=Kansas Supreme Court |accessdate=November 14, 2014}}</ref> until November 18, when the court ruled that Judge Moriarty was "within his jurisdiction" in ordering the issuance of marriage licenses to same-sex couples and lifted its stay.<ref>{{cite web|title=Order Lifting Johnson County Stay|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/247044630/112-590-Order-Lifting-Johnson-County-Stay|website=Scribd.com|accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> By that date, 19 Kansas counties were issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite web|title=Equality Kansas|url=https://www.facebook.com/EqualityKansas/posts/968729666474077|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref>

On November 19, District Court Judge [[Brian Morris]] ruled Montana's ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional in ''[[Rolando v. Fox]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Geidner|first1=Chris|title=Marriage Equality Comes To Montana, Federal Judge Rules|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/marriage-equality-comes-to-montana-federal-judge-rules|accessdate=November 20, 2014|work=BuzzFeed News|date=November 19, 2014}}</ref>

On November 20, the U.S. Supreme Court denied a request for a stay in a South Carolina case, allowing the district court's order prohibiting enforcement of the state's ban on same-sex marriage to take effect.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|title=Supreme Court won’t halt South Carolina same-sex marriages|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/11/20/supreme-court-wont-halt-south-carolina-sex-marriages/|accessdate=November 20, 2014|work=Washington Blade|date=November 20, 2014}}</ref> That same day, lawyers for the plaintiffs in a Louisiana case, [[Robicheaux v. Caldwell]] filed a petition for [[certiorari before judgment]] with the U.S. Supreme Court, citing the recent conflicting opinions on same-sex marriage in the federal circuit courts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Denniston|first1=Lyle|title=New same-sex marriage case at the Court|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2014/11/new-same-sex-marriage-case-at-the-court/|accessdate=November 20, 2014|work=SCOTUS Blog|date=November 20, 2014}}</ref>

