==Debate==

===Support===
{{See also|List of supporters of same-sex marriage in the United States}}
[[File:Garden State Equality May 2011 protest (5694200900).jpg|300px|thumb|left|2011 protest in [[New Jersey]] by [[Garden State Equality]] in support of marriage equality and against [[deportation]] of LGBT spouses.]]
Same-sex marriage supporters make several arguments in support of their position. [[Mark Mathabane|Gail Mathabane]] likens prohibitions on same-sex marriage to past U.S. prohibitions on [[Interracial marriage in the United States|interracial marriage]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/editorials/2004-01-25-couples_x.htm | work=USA Today | title=Gays face same battle interracial couples fought | first=Gail | last=Mathabane | date=January 25, 2004 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref> [[Fernando Espuelas]] argues that same-sex marriage should be allowed because same-sex marriage extends a civil right to a minority group.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/11/06/espuelas.prop.eight/ | publisher=CNN | title=Commentary: Latinos should see gay marriage a civil right - CNN.com | date=November 7, 2008 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref> According to an American history scholar, [[Nancy Cott]], "there really is no comparison, because there is nothing that is like marriage except marriage."<ref name="cott">[http://www.afer.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/Perry-Vol-1-1-11-10.pdf Direct Examination of Nancy Cott], p. 208. ''Perry v. Schwarzenegger'', No. 09-2292 (N.D. Cal. January 11, 2010). Retrieved December 20, 2011.</ref>

The [[Human Rights Campaign]] (HRC) is one of the leading advocacy groups in support of same-sex marriage. According to the HRC's website, "Many same-sex couples want the right to legally marry because they are in love—many, in fact, have spent the last 10, 20 or 50 years with that person—and they want to honor their relationship in the greatest way our society has to offer, by making a public commitment to stand together in good times and bad, through all the joys and challenges family life brings."<ref>[http://www.hrc.org/resources/entry/answers-to-questions-about-marriage-equality Human Rights Campaign website]. Retrieved November 1, 2010.</ref>

In the United States such professional organizations as the [[American Psychiatric Association]], [[American Psychological Association]], [[American Sociological Association]], [[American Medical Association]], [[American Academy of Pediatrics]], [[American Academy of Nursing]] and [[National Association of Social Workers]] have said that claims that the legal recognition of marriage for same–sex couples undermines the institution of marriage and harms children are inconsistent with the scientific evidence which supports the conclusions: that [[homosexuality]] is a normal expression of human sexuality that is not chosen; that gay and lesbian people form stable, committed relationships essentially equivalent to heterosexual relationships; that same-sex parents are no less capable than opposite-sex parents to raise children; and that the children of same-sex parents are no less psychologically healthy and well-adjusted than children of opposite-sex parents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdgln.com/news/2010/08/11/apa-reaffirms-support-same-sex-marriage|title=The APA reaffirms support for same-sex marriage|publisher=[[San Diego Gay and Lesbian News]]|date=|accessdate=July 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.psychiatry.org/File%20Library/Advocacy%20and%20Newsroom/Position%20Statements/ps2005_SameSexMarriage.pdf|title=Position Statement on Support of Legal Recognition of Same-Sex Civil Marriage|publisher=|date=|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psychiatry.org/File%20Library/Advocacy%20and%20Newsroom/Position%20Statements/ps2002_Adoption.pdf|title=Position Statement on Adoption and Co-parenting of Children by Same-sex Couples |publisher=American Psychiatric Association|year=2002|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ama-assn.org//ama/pub/about-ama/our-people/member-groups-sections/glbt-advisory-committee/ama-policy-regarding-sexual-orientation.page|title=AMA Policy Regarding Sexual Orientation|publisher=Ama-assn.org|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/118/1/349.full|title=The Effects of Marriage, Civil Union, and Domestic Partnership Laws on the Health and Well-being of Children|publisher=Pediatrics.aappublications.org|date=|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialworkers.org/diversity/lgb/062005.asp|title=Overview of Same Sex Marriage in the U.S.: The Struggle for Civil Rights and Equality|publisher=Socialworkers.org|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aannet.org/assets/docs/marriage%20equality_7-26%2012f.pdf|title=Support for Marriage Equality|publisher=American Academy of Nursing|date=July 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref> The body of research strongly supports the conclusion that discrimination by the federal government between married same-sex couples and married opposite-sex couples in granting benefits unfairly stigmatizes same-sex couples. The research also contradicts the stereotype-based rationales advanced to support passage of DOMA that the [[Equal Protection Clause]] was designed to prohibit.<ref name="amici2011">{{cite web|url=http://www.apa.org/about/offices/ogc/amicus/gill.pdf|title=Brief of the American Psychological Association, the Massachusetts Psychological Association, The National Association of Social Workers and its Massachusetts Chapter, the American Medical Association, and the American Academy of Pediatrics as Amici Curiae in Support of Plaintiffs-Appellees and in Support of Affirmance – Appeals from the United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts Civil Action Nos. 1:09-cv-11156-JLT, 1:09-cv-10309-JLT (Honorable Joseph L. Tauro)|format=PDF|accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref>

[[Garden State Equality]] of [[New Jersey]] states that the wording "same-sex marriage" implies a separate, and therefore unequal, category of marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gardenstateequality.org/issues/marriageequality/|title=Marriage Equality|publisher=Garden State Equality|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref> The 2012 Democratic Party Platform used the term "marriage equality" in its support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democrats.org/democratic-national-platform|title=The Democratic Party Platform|publisher=Democrats.org|date=|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref>

====Role of social media====
Supporters of the legalization of same-sex marriage have successfully used social media websites such as Facebook to help achieve that goal.<ref>Switzer, Cody. [http://philanthropy.com/article/Inside-the-Human-Rights/138423/ Inside the Human Rights Campaign's Social-Media Success] Philanthropy. April 9, 2013. Retrieved April 14, 2013.</ref><ref>Lipp, Murray. [http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/01/29/comment-the-power-of-online-activism-social-media-in-the-fight-for-lgbt-equality/ The power of online activism and social media in the fight for LGBT equality] Pink News. January 29, 2013. Accessed, April 14, 2013.</ref><ref>Royal, Denis. [http://southfloridagaynews.com/articles/facebook-page-gay-marriage-usa-pushes-for-equality/111659 Facebook Page 'Gay Marriage USA' Pushes for Equality] South Florida Gay News. April 10, 2013. Retrieved April 14, 2013.</ref> Some have argued that the successful use of social media websites by LGBT groups has played a key role in the defeat of religion-based opposition.<ref>Ferenstein, Gregory [http://techcrunch.com/2013/03/21/how-the-internet-is-erasing-the-religious-rights-political-power/ How The Internet Is Erasing The Religious Right’s Political Power] Tech Crunch. March 21, 2013. Retrieved April 14, 2013.</ref>

One of the largest scale uses of social media to mobilize support for same-sex marriage preceded and coincided with the arrival at the US Supreme Court of high-profile legal cases for Proposition 8 and the Defense of Marriage Act in March 2013. The 'red equals sign' project started by the Human Rights Campaign was an electronic campaign primarily based on Facebook which encouraged users to change their profile images to a red equal sign to express support for same-sex marriage.<ref>[http://www.hrc.org/blog/entry/slideshow-hrc-logo-memes HRC Logo Memes] Retrieved April 14, 2013.</ref> At the time of the court hearings it was estimated that approximately 2.5 million Facebook users changed their profile images to a red equals sign.<ref>Kleinman, Alexis [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/29/red-equal-sign-facebook_n_2980489.html How The Red Equal Sign Took Over Facebook, According To Facebook's Own Data] ''Huffington Post''. March 30, 2013. Retrieved April 14, 2013.</ref>

===Opposition===
[[File:Fresno - Prop 8 Rally.jpg|thumb|right|Rally for Prop 8 in Fresno, California (October 2008)]]
{{See also|List of opponents of same-sex marriage in the United States}}

Opponents of same-sex marriage in the United States ground their arguments on parenting concerns, religious concerns, concerns that changes to the definition of marriage would lead to the inclusion of polygamy or incest, and in natural law-based reasoning.<ref>{{cite web|title=Homosexuality|url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/homosexuality/#NatLaw|work=Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|publisher=stanford.edu|accessdate=May 8, 2012}}</ref> The Southern Baptist Convention adopted a statement in June 2003 that legalizing same-sex relationships would "convey a societal approval of a homosexual lifestyle, which the Bible calls sinful and dangerous both to the individuals involved and to society at large".<ref>{{cite web|title=On Same-Sex Marriage, June 2003|url=http://www.sbc.net/resolutions/amResolution.asp?ID=1128|date=August 19, 2013|publisher=Southern Baptist Convention}}</ref> [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], the [[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]], the [[Southern Baptist Convention]], and [[National Organization for Marriage]] claim that children do best when raised by a mother and father, and that legalizing same-sex marriage is, therefore, contrary to the best interests of children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/the-divine-institution-of-marriage|title=The Divine Institution of Marriage – LDS Newsroom|publisher=Beta-newsroom.lds.org|date=August 13, 2008|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usccb.org/about/laity-marriage-family-life-and-youth/manandwoman.shtml|title=(FLWY)|publisher=USCCB|date=November 12, 2003|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gofbw.com/News.asp?id=11943|title=Obama celebrates gay dads on Father's Day – Florida Baptist Witness|publisher=Gofbw.com|date=July 2, 2010|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationformarriage.org/atf/cf/%7B39D8B5C1-F9FE-48C0-ABE6-1029BA77854C%7D/ProtestantEnglish.pdf|title=Why Marriage Matters|format=PDF|date=|accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref> [[Maggie Gallagher]] of the National Organization for Marriage has raised concerns about the impact of same-sex marriage upon religious liberty and upon faith-based charities in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/012/191kgwgh.asp|title=Banned in Boston|work=[[The Weekly Standard]]|date=May 15, 2006|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref>
Opponents of same-sex marriage have claimed that redefining marriage to include same-sex relationships would have harmful effects on biological family, children's rights, and social welfare.<ref>{{cite web|last=George et al.|first=Robert P.|title=What is Marriage|url=https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1722155|work=Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy|accessdate=March 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Le Fevre|first=Tyler A.|title=Gender and the Institutional Nature of Marriage|url=http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2407789|accessdate=March 20, 2014}}</ref> Stanley Kurtz of the ''Weekly Standard'' has written that same-sex marriage would eventually lead to the legalization of [[polygamy]] and [[polyamory]], or [[group marriage]], in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/002/938xpsxy.asp|title=Beyond Gay Marriage|work=[[The Weekly Standard]]|date=August 4, 2003|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref>

The funding of the amendment referendum campaigns has been an issue of great dispute. Both judges<ref name="boston">[http://bangordailynews.com/2012/02/01/news/state/anti-gay-marriage-group-loses-maine-list-appeal/ Anti-gay marriage group loses Maine appeal to prevent release of its donor list]. David Sharp, Associated Press, January 31, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jurist.org/forum/2012/01/joshua-douglas-citizens-united.php|title=Campaign Finance After Two Years of Citizens United, Josh Douglas of the University of Kentucky College of Law, January 21, 2012|publisher=Jurist.org|date=January 21, 2012|accessdate=May 19, 2012}}</ref> and the IRS<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/13/business/13gift.html I.R.S. Moves to Tax Gifts to Groups Active in Politics, New York Times, By Stephanie Strom, May 12, 2011]</ref> have ruled that it is either questionable or illegal for campaign contributions to be shielded by anonymity. In February 2012, the [[National Organization for Marriage]] vowed to spend $250,000 in Washington legislative races to defeat the Republican state senators who voted for same-sex marriage.<ref>[http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/02/03/us-gay-marriage-washington-idUSTRE81204O20120203 Gay marriage foes to fight expected Washington state law]. Nicole Neroulias, Reuters, February 2, 2012.</ref>

===Politicians and media figures===
[[File:Robin Roberts interviewing Barack Obama.jpg|right|thumb|President Barack Obama interviewed by [[Robin Roberts (newscaster)|Robin Roberts]] of ABC's ''[[Good Morning America]]'', in the Cabinet Room of the White House, May 9, 2012.]]
President [[Barack Obama|Obama]]'s [[Social policy of Barack Obama#Same-sex marriage|views on same-sex marriage]] have varied over the course of his political career and become more consistently supportive of same-sex marriage rights over time. In the 1990s, he had supported same-sex marriage while campaigning for the Illinois Senate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/01/15/report-obama-changed-view-gay-marriage/|title=Report: Obama Changed His View on Gay Marriage |publisher=FoxNews.com |date=April 7, 2010|accessdate=June 27, 2010}}</ref><ref name="huffingtonpost.com">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/01/13/obama-once-supported-same_n_157656.html|title=Obama Once Supported Same-Sex Marriage 'Unequivocally'|publisher=Huffingtonpost.com|date= January 13, 2009|accessdate=December 20, 2011|first=Jason |last=Linkins}}</ref> During the 2008 presidential campaign, he said: "I believe that marriage is the union between a man and a woman. For me as a Christian, it is a sacred union. You know, God is in the mix."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/The-Vote/2009/0512/obama-and-miss-california-aligned-on-same-sex-marriage |title=Obama and Miss California aligned on same-sex marriage?|work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|date=May 12, 2009 |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> He opposed the 2008 [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|California referendum]] that aimed at reversing a court ruling establishing same-sex marriage there.<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael D.|last=Shear|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/08/05/AR2010080502211.html|title=President Obama's beliefs meet his policy|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 5, 2010|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> In 2009, he opposed two opposing federal legislative proposals that would have banned or established same-sex marriage nationally, stating that each state had to decide the issue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.com/news/2009/jan/13/gay-supporters-petition-obama-repeal-doma/|title=Gay Supporters Petition Obama to Repeal DOMA|date=January 13, 2009|accessdate=June 24, 2009|first=Penny|last=Paterson|publisher=[[Santa Barbara Independent]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Eleveld|first=Kerry |title=White House Responds to Iowa|publisher=[[The Advocate]]|date=April 3, 2009|url=http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid77464.asp|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> In December 2010, he expressed support for civil unions with rights equivalent to marriage and for federal recognition of same-sex relationships. He opposed a federal constitutional amendment to ban same-sex marriage.<ref name=whitehouse>{{cite web|title=Civil Rights|url= http://www.whitehouse.gov/issues/civil-rights/|publisher=The White House|accessdate=October 3, 2009}}</ref> He also stated that his position on same-sex marriage was "evolving" and that he recognized that civil unions from the perspective of same-sex couples was "not enough".<ref name="wapo">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/23/AR2010122301859.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|title=Obama says his views on same-sex marriage are evolving|accessdate=January 5, 2011|first=Perry|last=Bacon, Jr.|date=December 23, 2010}}</ref> On May 9, 2012, President Obama became the first sitting president to say he believed that same-sex couples should be allowed to marry. He still said the legal question belonged to the states.<ref name="obamasupport-ABCNews" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-05-09/news/sns-rt-us-usa-campaign-obama-gaymarriagebre84818y-20120509_1_gay-marriage-civil-unions-lesbian-couples |title=Same-sex couples should be able to marry: Obama|first=Jeff|last=Mason |work=Chicago Tribune|date=May 9, 2012|accessdate=March 20, 2013}}</ref> In October 2014, Obama told an interviewer that his view had changed:<ref>{{cite web|last1=Toobin|first1=Jeffrey|title=The Obama Brief|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/10/27/obama-brief |work=The New Yorker|accessdate=October 20, 2014|date=October 27, 2014}}</ref>
{{quote|Ultimately, I think the [[Equal Protection Clause]] does guarantee same-sex marriage in all fifty states. But, as you know, courts have always been strategic. There have been times where the stars were aligned and the Court, like a thunderbolt, issues a ruling like [[Brown v. Board of Education]], but that's pretty rare. And, given the direction of society, for the Court to have allowed the process to play out the way it has may make the shift less controversial and more lasting.}}

Former presidents [[Bill Clinton]]<ref>{{cite news|date=May 5, 2011|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/onpolitics/post/2011/05/bill-clinton-endorses-gay-marriage-in-new-york-/|title=Bill Clinton endorses gay marriage in New York|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=June 26, 2012}}</ref> and [[Jimmy Carter]],<ref>{{cite news|date=March 19, 2012|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/19/president-jimmy-carter-bible-book_n_1349570.html|title=President Jimmy Carter Authors New Bible Book, Answers Hard Biblical Questions|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 26, 2012|first=Paul|last=Raushenbush}}</ref> former vice presidents [[Dick Cheney]]<ref>{{cite news|date=September 13, 2011|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/09/13/dick-cheney-gay-marriage_n_960874.html|title=Dick Cheney On Gay Marriage: "I Certainly Don't Have Any Problem With It|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 26, 2012|first=Timothy|last=Stenovec}}</ref> and [[Al Gore]],<ref>{{cite web|date=January 17, 2008|url=http://current.com/items/88817757_gay-men-and-women-should-have-the-same-rights.htm|title=Al Gore: "Gay men and women should have the same rights|publisher=[[Current TV]]|accessdate=July 8, 2012}}</ref> [[Walter Mondale]]<ref name="Mondale">{{cite web|last=Mondale|first=Walter|title=Mondale and Dukakis Back Marriage Equality|publisher=[[ThinkProgress]]|date=May 16, 2013|url=http://thinkprogress.org/lgbt/2013/05/16/2021841/mondale-dukakis-back-marriage-equality/?mobile=nc|accessdate=June 20, 2013}}</ref> and current Vice President [[Joe Biden]] have voiced their support for legal recognition, as have former first ladies [[Laura Bush]]<ref>Wing, Nick. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/05/13/laura-bush-gay-marriage-s_n_574731.html Laura Bush: Gay Marriage Should Be Legal, Abortion Should Remain Legal (VIDEO)]. ''The Huffington Post''. May 13, 2011. Retrieved March 27, 2013.</ref> and [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>Wing, Nick. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/18/hillary-clinton-gay-marriage_n_2900557.html Hillary Clinton Announces Support For Gay Marriage]. ''The Huffington Post''. March 18, 2013. Retrieved March 27, 2013.</ref> Former president [[George H. W. Bush]] and his wife [[Barbara Bush|Barbara]] have served as witnesses to a same-sex wedding, but neither has publicly stated whether this means they support same-sex marriage in general.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Washington Post|url=http://m.washingtonpost.com/blogs/reliable-source/wp/2013/09/25/george-h-w-bush-is-witness-at-same-sex-marriage-in-maine/ |date=September 25, 2013|accessdate=March 17, 2014|title=George H.W. Bush is Witness at Same-Sex Marriage in Maine }}</ref> In May 2012, [[Barack Obama]] became the first sitting President to support same-sex marriage.<ref name="obamasupport-ABCNews" />  Fifteen [[U.S. Senator|U.S. senators]] announced their support in the spring of 2013.<ref>Wilson, Chris. [http://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/same-sex-marriage-senate-endorsement-tracker-154748412--politics.html The same-sex marriage Senate endorsement tracker]. Yahoo! News. Updated June 19, 2013. Retrieved June 27, 2013.</ref> By April 2013 a majority of the Senate had expressed support for same-sex marriage.<ref name="Majority of Senators">{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Sunlen|title=Majority of Senate Supports Same Sex Marriage |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2013/04/another-gop-senator-endorses-same-sex-marriage/|accessdate=June 26, 2013|newspaper=ABC News|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref> Senator [[Rob Portman]] of Ohio became the first sitting Republican senator to endorse same-sex marriage in March 2013,<ref>Stein, Sam. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/25/rob-portman-gay-marriage_n_2947796.html Rob Portman's Gay Marriage Conversion Explained By His Son]. ''The Huffington Post''. March 25, 2013. Retrieved June 26, 2013.</ref> followed by Senator [[Mark Kirk]] of Illinois in April,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/andrewkaczynski/republican-sen-mark-kirk-endorses-marriage-equality |first=Andrew|last= Kaczynski |accessdate=September 28, 2014|title=Republican Sen. Mark Kirk Endorses Marriage Equality |date=April 2, 2013 |work=Buzzfeed}}</ref> [[Lisa Murkowski]] of Alaska in June,<ref name="Murkowski">{{cite news|last=Burgess|first=Everett |title=Lisa Murkowski Endorses Same Sex Marriage|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/06/lisa-murkowski-gay-marriage-stance-93047.html|accessdate=June 26, 2013|newspaper=Politico|date=June 19, 2013}}</ref> and [[Susan Collins]] of Maine a year later.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moretto|first=Mario|title=Susan Collins becomes fourth GOP senator to publicly support same-sex marriage|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2014/06/25/politics/elections/susan-collins-i-support-same-sex-marriage/|work=Bangor Daily News|accessdate=June 25, 2014|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref>

During the 2008 presidential election campaign, Republican Vice Presidential candidate [[Sarah Palin]] stated: "I have voted along with the vast majority of Alaskans who had the opportunity to vote to amend our Constitution defining marriage as between one man and one woman. I wish on a federal level that that's where we would go because I don't support gay marriage."<ref>Scott Conroy, "[http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-502443_162-4531945-502443.html Palin Breaks With McCain On Gay Marriage Ban]", CBS News, October 20, 2008. Retrieved October 31, 2010.</ref>

When a U.S. district court invalidated the [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|California referendum]] that ended same-sex marriages there in 2008, former Speaker of the House [[Newt Gingrich]] said it showed "an outrageous disrespect for our Constitution and for the majority of people of the United States who believe marriage is the union of husband and wife".<ref>{{cite news|title=California's Same-Sex Marriage Ban Overturned in Court Ruling|url=http://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/california-same-sex-marriage-verdict/|accessdate=September 28, 2014|work=PBS Newshour|date=August 4, 2010}}</ref> By the end of 2012, Gingrich was prepared to accept civil—but not religious—same-sex marriages and encouraged the Republican Party to accept the fact of same-sex marriage was certain to become legal in more and more states.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1= Sam |last2=Ward |first2=Jon |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/20/newt-gingrich-mitt-romney_n_2337895.html |title=Newt Gingrich On Mitt Romney: 'I Would Have Probably Done Better' Against Obama| work=Huffington Post|date= December 20, 2012| accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>

In an interview on ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'' in August 2010, when [[Glenn Beck]] was asked if he "believe(s) that gay marriage is a threat to [this] country in any way", he stated, "No I don't...I believe that [[Thomas Jefferson]] said: 'If it neither breaks my leg nor picks my pocket what difference is it to me?'"<ref>Elizabeth Tenety, "[http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/undergod/2010/08/glenn_beck_gay_marriage_advocate.html Glenn Beck, Gay Marriage Advocate?]", ''[[The Washington Post]]'', August 12, 2010. Retrieved October 31, 2010.</ref><ref>''Talkers Magazine'', {{Wayback |date=20110130043748 |url=http://talkers.com/online/?p=3774 |title="2010 Talkers 250"}}. Retrieved November 30, 2010.</ref>

On his radio show in August 2010, commentator [[Rush Limbaugh]] said: "Marriage? There's a definition of it, for it. It means something. Marriage is a union of a man and woman. It's always been that. If you want to get married and you're a man, marry a woman. Nobody's stopping you. This is about tearing apart an institution."<ref>Limbaugh, Rush (August 5, 2010). [http://www.rushlimbaugh.com/daily/2010/08/05/one_leftist_judge_slaps_down_seven_million_voters_in_california "One Leftist Judge Slaps Down Seven Million Voters in California"]. Retrieved October 31, 2010.</ref>

==Public opinion==
{{Main|Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States}}
{{update|section||date=October 2014}}

[[File:Public opinion of same-sex marriage in USA by state.svg|thumb||400px|Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States of America {{legend|#00008B|A poll reports a [[1.96|significant]] finding that a majority of that state's population supports same-sex marriage.<br>(95% significant: Result is > 0.653 of the 95% sampling error (> 1.28σ) above 50%.)}}
