Only the case before the highest court is coded per state.<!--Asterisk: The state attorney-general is not defending the ban.-->]]

Lawsuits have been filed in state and federal courts to challenge same-sex marriage bans in every state that prohibits the issuance of marriage licenses to same-sex couples or the recognition of same-sex marriages performed elsewhere,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Snow|first1=Justin|title=With North Dakota lawsuit, all state gay marriage bans challenged |url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/06/with-north-dakota-lawsuit-all-state-gay-marriage-bans-challenged/|accessdate=September 18, 2014|work=Metro Weekly|date=June 6, 2014}}</ref> as well as in Puerto Rico.

===U.S. Supreme Court===
On October 6, 2014, the U.S. Supreme Court denied [[certiorari]] without recorded dissent in all the cases it had been asked to consider from appellate courts in the Fourth, Seventh, and Tenth Circuits, allowing the circuit court decisions striking down marriage bans to stand. The cases were: ''[[Baskin v. Bogan|Bogan v. Baskin]]'' (Indiana); ''[[Wolf v. Walker|Walker v. Wolf]]'' (Wisconsin); ''[[Herbert v. Kitchen]]'' (Utah); ''[[Bostic v. Schaefer|McQuigg v. Bostic]]'' (Virginia); ''[[Bostic v. Rainey|Rainey v. Bostic]]'' (Virginia); ''[[Bostic v. Schaefer|Schaefer v. Bostic]]'' (Virginia); and ''[[Bishop v. United States|Smith v. Bishop]]'' (Oklahoma).<ref name=scotusdecline/> On November 13, commenting in an unrelated case on behalf of himself and Justice [[Antonin Scalia]], Justice [[Clarence Thomas]] wrote that the Supreme Court "often review[s] decisions striking down state laws, even in the absence of a disagreement among lower courts.... But for reasons that escape me, we have not done so with any consistency, especially in recent months". He referenced denials of certiorari or denials of a stay in ''Herbert'', ''Bishop'', ''Bostic'', ''Walker v. Wolf'', ''Otter v. Latta'', and ''Parnell v. Hamby''.<ref>{{cite web|title=On Application for Stay: ''Maricopa County v. Lopez-Valenzuela''|url=http://sblog.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Arizona-Prop.-100-stay-denial1.pdf|publisher=U.S. Supreme Court|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref>

;''[[Bourke v. Beshear]]'' and ''[[Love v. Beshear]]'' (Kentucky)
:Filed on July 26, 2013; the U.S. district court found the state's refusal to recognize same-sex marriages from other jurisdictions an unconstitutional violation of the equal protection clause and stayed enforcement of its decision during appeal. After additional plaintiffs joined the lawsuit to challenge the state's denial of marriage licenses to same-sex couples, the court divided the case. ''Love'' continued in district court as to the state marriage license issue, while the out-of-state recognition issue was appealed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomaston |first=Scottie |title=Kentucky marriage equality case re-named Love v. Beshear|url=http://equalityontrial.com/2014/02/28/kentucky-marriage-equality-case-re-named-love-v-beshear/|accessdate=February 28, 2014|newspaper=Equality on Trial|date=February 28, 2014}}</ref> On July 1, 2014, U.S. District Judge [[John G. Heyburn II]] found in favor of the intervening plaintiffs and ruled that Kentucky's denial of marriage licenses to same-sex couples violates the equal protection clause. He found that homosexual persons constitute a [[suspect class]] deserving [[heightened scrutiny]] and suggested the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|Sixth Circuit]] should adopt that standard of review. He found Kentucky's ban did not withstand even [[rational basis review|rational basis]] review.<ref>{{cite news|last1=John E. Heyburn II, U.S. District Judge|title=Memorandum Opinion and Order, ''Love v. Beshear'', No. 3:13-CV-750-H |url=http://cdn.lgbtqnation.com/assets/2014/07/ky-marriage-ruling-070114.pdf|author2=[[U.S. District Court for the Western District of Kentucky]]|publisher=LBGTQ Nation.com|date=July 1, 2014|ref=Love-Opinion}}</ref> He stayed his ruling pending appeal. The Sixth Circuit consolidated ''Love v. Beshear'' with ''Bourke v. Beshear''. The Sixth Circuit reversed the district court and upheld Kentucky's ban on same sex marriage on November 6.<ref name=sixthupholds/> The couples filed an application for certiorari with the U.S. Supreme Court on November 17.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kentucky Plaintiffs' Cert Petition|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/246887775/Kentucky-Plaintiffs-Cert-Petition|website=Scribd.com|accessdate=November 17, 2014}}</ref>

;''[[DeBoer v. Snyder]]'' (Michigan)
:Filed on January 23, 2012; the U.S. district court found that the state ban violates the equal protection clause, 973 F. Supp. 2d 757 (E.D. Mich.) and issued a permanent injunction against enforcement of the state's same-sex marriage ban on March 21, 2014. The Sixth Circuit issued a stay pending appeal, on a 2–1 vote agreed to expedite the appeal, and denied the state's petition for an initial hearing ''[[en banc]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hunt, Deborah, Court Clerk|title=Order (denying initial ''en banc'' hearing), ''DeBoer v. Snyder'', No. 14-1341|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/220825608/14-1341-42-ORDER-Denying-en-banc|accessdate=May 7, 2014|author2=U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|publisher=Scribd.com|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref> The Sixth Circuit reversed the district court and upheld Michigan's ban on same sex marriage on November 6<ref name=sixthupholds/> and the same-sex couples filed an application for certiorari with the U.S. Supreme Court on November 17.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michigan Plaintiffs' Cert Petition|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/246883477/Michigan-Plaintiffs-Cert-Petition|website=Scribd.com|accessdate=November 17, 2014}}</ref>

;''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' and ''[[Henry v. Hodges]]'' (Ohio)
:In a case filed on July 19, 2013, originally ''Obergefell v. Wymyslo'', the U.S. district court found that the state ban on same-sex marriage violates the due process clause, for the limited purpose of issuing death certificates. On February 10, 2014, four same-sex couples legally married in other states filed suit in U.S. district court asking that Ohio be required to record the names of both same-sex parents on their children's birth certificates. They amended their suit to challenge the state's denial of marriage rights to same-sex couples. On April 14, 2014, District Court Judge [[Timothy Black]], ruling in ''Henry v. Himes'', ordered the state to record the plaintiffs' names on their children's birth certificates, but stayed further enforcement of his decision pending appeal. On May 29, 2014, the Sixth Circuit consolidated ''Obergefell'' and ''Henry''. The Sixth Circuit reversed the district court and upheld Ohio's ban on same sex marriage on November 6,<ref name=sixthupholds/> and the same-sex couples filed an application for certiorari with the U.S. Supreme Court on November 14.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/11/same-sex-marriage-back-before-the-supreme-court/ |first=Justin|last=Snow |work=Metro Weekly| date=November 14, 2014|accessdate=November 14, 2014| title= Same-sex marriage back before the Supreme Court}}</ref>

;''[[Tanco v. Haslam]]'' (Tennessee)
:Filed on October 21, 2013; the U.S. district court granted a preliminary injunction on March 14, 2014, after finding the equal protection analysis in ''Bourke'' persuasive. The injunction required Tennessee to recognize the three plaintiff same-sex couples' out-of-state marriages until the court disposes of the case; it also indicated that the couples are likely to succeed on the merits of their case. The district judge denied Tennessee's motion to stay the injunction, reasoning that unlike ''Kitchen v. Herbert'' (where the U.S. Supreme Court granted a stay) this injunction covers only three couples and not the entire state. The Sixth Circuit granted a stay at the request of the state defendants and ordered expedited assignment to a panel of judges for consideration on the merits.<ref name=145297CA6Order042514>{{cite news|last=Guy and Clay, Circuit Judges; Bertlesman, District Judge (sitting by designation)|title=Order (granting stay, assignment to merits panel), ''Tanco v. Haslam'', No. 14-5297|url=http://www.tn.gov/attorneygeneral/cases/tanco/tancoorder-4-25-2014.pdf|accessdate=May 1, 2014|publisher=U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|date=April 25, 2014}}</ref> The Sixth Circuit reversed the district court and upheld Tennessee's ban on same sex marriage on November 6,<ref name=sixthupholds/> and the same-sex couples filed an application for certiorari with the U.S. Supreme Court on November 14.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tanco v. Haslam, Plaintiffs' Petition for Writ of Certiorari|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/246621684/Tennessee-Plaintiffs-Cert-Petition|website=Scribd.com|accessdate=November 14, 2014}}</ref>

===Courts of Appeals===
[[File:US Court of Appeals and District Court map.svg|thumb|Federal courts of appeal (numbered) and federal district courts (dashed lines and state boundaries)]]

====First Circuit====
;''[[Conde-Vidal v. Garcia-Padilla]]'' (Puerto Rico)
:Same-sex marriage lawsuit filed in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]] in late March 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/puerto-rican-sex-marriages-recognized-23067316|agency=ABC News|title=Puerto Rican Wants Same-Sex Marriages Recognized|date=March 26, 2014|accessdate=March 30, 2014}}</ref> On October 21, Judge [[Juan Manuel Perez-Gimenez|Juan M. Perez-Gimenez]] dismissed the suit, citing the U.S. Supreme Court's dismissal of ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'' in 1972: "the plaintiffs constitutional claims challenging the Puerto Rico Civil Code's recognition of opposite-gender marriage fail to present a substantial federal question".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris |title=Judge upholds Puerto Rico ban on same-sex marriage |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/10/21/judge-upholds-puerto-rico-ban-sex-marriage/|accessdate=October 12, 2014 |work=Washington Blade|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> [[Lambda Legal]] filed a notice of appeal with the [[Court of Appeals for the First Circuit|First Circuit Court of Appeals]] on October 28.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Denniston |first1=Lyle|title=Testing the status of ''Baker v. Nelson''|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2014/10/testing-the-status-of-baker-v-nelson/ |accessdate=October 28, 2014|work=SCOTUSblog|date=October 28, 2014}}</ref>

====Fourth Circuit====
;''[[General Synod of the United Church of Christ v. Cooper]]'' (North Carolina)
:On April 28, 2014, the [[United Church of Christ]], joined by a coalition of Baptists and Lutherans, filed a lawsuit<ref>{{cite web|title=General Synod of the United Church of Christ v. Cooper|url=http://www.amendmentonelawsuit.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Complaint-filed-on-April-28.pdf|accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref> arguing that North Carolina is unconstitutionally restricting religious freedom by criminalizing its clergy members for blessing same-sex marriages.<ref>{{cite web|title=North Carolina's Gay-Marriage Ban Is Challenged by Church|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/29/us/churchs-lawsuit-challenges-north-carolina-ban-on-same-sex-marriage.html|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref> On July 28, 2014, following the ruling by the Fourth Circuit of Appeals in ''Bostic'' that Virginia's ban on same-sex marriage is unconstitutional, Attorney General Roy Cooper announced he would stop defending North Carolina's same-sex marriage ban.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lachman |first= Samantha | title = North Carolina Attorney General To Stop Defending State's Gay Marriage Ban |work= Huffington Post |accessdate= October 8, 2014| date= July 28, 2014| url= http://m.huffpost.com/us/entry/5628129 }}</ref> On October 10, District Court Judge [[Max O. Cogburn]] ruled the state's ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Snow|first1=Justin |title=Federal judge strikes down North Carolina same-sex marriage ban|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/10/federal-judge-strikes-down-north-carolina-same-sex-marriage-ban/|accessdate=October 10, 2014|work=Metro Weekly|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> When the named state defendants did not appeal, Thom Tillis and Phil Berger, each the leader of a house of the state legislature, asked to be allowed to intervene and appeal the district court's decision.<ref>{{cite web|title=Notice of Appeal|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/245878166/3-14-cv-00213-124|website=Scribd.com|accessdate=November 17, 2014}}</ref>
;''[[Condon v. Haley]]'' (South Carolina)
:On October 15, 2014, a lesbian couple represented by Lambda Legal and South Carolina Equality filed suit in federal district court seeking the right to marry, citing ''Bostic''. The defendants include the governor, the attorney general, and Judge Irvin G. Condon, the state judge who was enjoined from licensing same-sex marriages a week earlier by the South Carolina Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|title=Complaint, October 15, 2014|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/243112181/Condon-v-Haley-Complaint|website=Scribd.com|publisher=U.S. District Court for South Carolina|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> Judge [[Richard Gergel]] ruled for the plaintiffs on November 12 and stayed his ruling until noon on November 20.<ref name=SCstrike/> The state defendants filed a notice of appeal and asked the Fourth Circuit to issue a stay pending appeal or a temporary stay,<ref>{{cite web|title=Motion for Emergency Stay|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/246503547/14-2241-6-Motion-for-Stay |publisher=Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref> both of which the Fourth Circuit denied on November 18.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stay Denied|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/247034008/14-2241-14-Stay-Denied |website=Scribd.com |accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> Attorney General [[Alan Wilson]] asked Chief Justice [[John Roberts]], as Circuit Justice for the Fourth Circuit, for an emergency stay pending appeal later that day.<ref>{{cite web |title=South Carolina Stay Application|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/247059124/14A533-South-Carolina-Stay-Application |website=Scribd.com |accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> Justice Roberts referred the request to the full court, which denied it on November 20 with Justices Scalia and Thomas dissenting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/112014zr_bq7c.pdf |publisher=Supreme Court of the United States|date=November 20, 2014| title = Order in Pending Case |accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref>

====Fifth Circuit====
The Fifth Circuit has scheduled oral argument in ''[[De Leon v. Perry]]'' and ''[[Robicheaux v. Caldwell|Robicheaux v. George]]'' for January 9, 2015.

;''[[De Leon v. Perry]]'' (Texas)
:Filed on October 28, 2013; preliminary injunction granted in U.S. district court on February 26, 2014. The district judge issued a stay pending appeal.<ref>{{cite news|author=Fernandez, Manny|title=Federal Judge Strikes Down Texas' Ban on Same-Sex Marriage|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/27/us/texas-judge-strikes-down-state-ban-on-same-sex-marriage.html |accessdate=March 10, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 26, 2014}}</ref> Circuit Judge [[James E. Graves, Jr.]] denied without comment the plaintiffs motion for an expedited hearing of the appeal on May 21.<ref>{{cite news|last=Graves |first=James E. (U.S. Circuit Judge)|title=Order (Denying Motion to Expedite), ''De Leon v. Perry'', No. 14-50196|publisher=[[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]]|date=May 21, 2014}}</ref> He approved expedited oral argument on October 7.<ref>{{cite web|title=Order Expediting Oral Argument|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/242216096/14-50196-Order-Expediting-Oral-Argument|website=Scribd.com|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref>

;''[[Robicheaux v. Caldwell|Robicheaux v. George]]'' (Louisiana)
:A marriage recognition case, filed in July 2013, was later joined by plaintiffs from another case, refiled with additional defendants, and titled ''Robicheaux v. Caldwell''. Oral arguments on the recognition of marriages from other jurisdictions were held on June 25, 2014, before U.S. District Judge [[Martin Leach-Cross Feldman|Martin Feldman]], who scheduled further briefing on the broader question of the state's ban on same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGill|first1=Kevin |title=Judge in La. same-sex marriage case signals he may expand scope of ruling|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2014/06/judge-in-la-same-sex-marriage-case-signals-he-may-expand-scope-of-ruling/|work=LGBTQNation.com|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref> On September 3, Judge Feldman ruled against the plaintiffs, upholding Louisiana's ban on same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robertson|first1=Campbell |title=Federal Judge, Bucking Trend, Affirms Ban on Same-Sex Marriages in Louisiana |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/us/louisiana-gay-marriage-ban-upheld-by-federal-judge.html|accessdate=September 20, 2014|work=New York Times|date=September 3, 2014}}</ref> Plaintiffs appealed, and on September 25, U.S. Circuit Judge [[Jerry Edwin Smith]] set an expedited briefing schedule to allow the case to be heard by the same panel and at the same time as a similar Texas case, ''[[De Leon v. Perry]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Denniston |first1=Lyle|title=Texas, Louisiana same-sex marriage cases linked|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2014/09/texas-louisiana-same-sex-marriage-cases-linked/ |accessdate= September 26, 2014|work=SCOTUSblog|date=September 25, 2014}}</ref> Briefing was scheduled to conclude on November 7.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pertuit|first1=Shea (Deputy Clerk of Court)|title=''Robicheaux v. Caldwell'', No. 14-31037 |url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/241010156/14-31037-Briefing-Schedule|publisher=[[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit]] |publisher=Scribd.com|date=25 September 2014}}</ref> On November 20, the plaintiffs filed a petition asking the U.S. Supreme Court for a writ of certiorari before judgment, that is, to hear the case, now ''Robicheaux v. George'', without waiting for a decision from the Fifth Circuit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Geidner|first1=Chris|title=Louisiana Same-Sex Couples Ask Supreme Court To Hear Their Marriage Case|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/louisiana-same-sex-couples-ask-supreme-court-to-hear-their-m|accessdate=November 20, 2014|work=BuzzFeed News|date=November 20, 2014}}</ref>

====Sixth Circuit====
The [[Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals]] heard oral arguments in cases from four states (''DeBoer'', ''Obergefell'' and ''Henry'', ''Bourke'' and ''Love'', and ''Tanco'') on August 6, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Keen|first1=Lisa|title=Sixth Circuit GOP judges: Why not let the voters decide who gets to marry?|url=http://www.keennewsservice.com/2014/08/07/sixth-circuit-gop-judges-why-not-let-the-voters-decide-who-gets-to-marry/|accessdate=August 14, 2014|agency=Keen News Service |date=August 7, 2014}}</ref> On November 6, it upheld bans on same-sex marriage in Kentucky, Michigan, Ohio, and Tennessee.<ref name=sixthupholds>{{cite news|last1=Geidner|first1=Chris|title=Federal Appeals Court Upholds Four States' Same-Sex Marriage Bans |url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/federal-appeals-court-upholds-michigan-same-sex-marriage-ban|accessdate=November 6, 2014|work=BuzzFeed News|date=November 6, 2014}}</ref> The cases from all four states have since been petitioned to the Supreme Court.

====Ninth Circuit====
;''[[Hamby v. Parnell]]'' (Alaska)
:On October 12, 2014, Judge [[Timothy Mark Burgess|Timothy M. Burgess]] ruled the Alaska ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional. The injunction was not stayed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Boots|first1=Michelle Theriault|title=Federal judge rules Alaska's same-sex marriage ban unconstitutional|url=http://www.adn.com/article/20141012/federal-judge-rules-alaskas-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional|accessdate=October 13, 2014|work=Alaska Dispatch News|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> State officials have appealed and the Ninth Circuit has set a briefing schedule to be completed in February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Time Schedule Order, October 14, 2014|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/242978136/14-35856-1-Scheduling-Order|publisher=U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|accessdate=October 14, 2014}}</ref> On October 22, the appellants asked the Ninth Circuit for an initial hearing ''en banc'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Appellants' Petition for Initial ''en banc'' Hearing|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/244032678/14-35856-7|website=Scribd.com|publisher=Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref> which the Circuit rejected without dissent on November 19.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=November 20, 2014|date=November 19, 2014|url=http://www.trialinsider.com/?p=5321| first=Pamela A. |last=MacLean|title=Alaska Loses Round in Gay Marriage Appeal |work=Trial Insider}}</ref>

;''[[Latta v. Otter]]'' (Idaho) and ''[[Sevcik v. Sandoval]]'' (Nevada)
:In a single decision on October 7, 2014, the Ninth Circuit ruled that Idaho's and Nevada's bans on same-sex marriage are unconstitutional. It applied that circuit's recent ruling that discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation is subject to [[heightened scrutiny]] review.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Denniston|first1=Lyle|title=Two more bans fall |url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2014/10/two-more-bans-fall/|accessdate=October 20, 2014|work=SCOTUSblog|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> Nevada began licensing and recognizing same-sex marriages on October 9, Idaho on October 15. On October 13, the Coalition for the Protection of Marriage, which had been allowed to intervene to defend Nevada's ban in ''Sevcik'', petitioned the Ninth Circuit for rehearing ''en banc'', and on October 21 Idaho Governor Otter did likewise. On October 22, the Ninth Circuit asked the original plaintiffs in both cases to respond in 21 days.<ref>{{cite web|title=Parties to respond to Coalition's petition for rehearing en banc|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/244026639/12-17668-277|publisher=Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals |accessdate=October 22, 2014|website=Scribd.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Order: Plaintiffs-Appellees to response to petition for rehearing en banc|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/244026188/14-35420-202|publisher=Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals |accessdate=October 22, 2014|website=Scribd.com}}</ref>

====Tenth Circuit====
;''[[Same-sex marriage in Kansas#Marie v. Moser|Marie v. Moser]]'' (Kansas)
:The ACLU filed this lawsuit in the [[U.S. District Court for the District of Kansas|U.S. District of Kansas]] on October 10, 2014, on behalf of two lesbian couples who had been refused marriage licenses. The suit named as defendants Robert Moser, Secretary of the Kansas Department of Health and Environment, and two district court clerks.<ref name="Complaint, October 10, 2014"/> Judge [[Daniel D. Crabtree]] heard oral arguments on October 31.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hanna|first1=John|title=Kansas Urges Judge Not to Rule on Gay Marriage|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/judge-hold-hearing-kansas-gay-marriage-suit-26592616|accessdate=October 31, 2014|work=ABC News|agency=Associated Press|date=October 31, 2014}}</ref> On November 4, 2014, he ruled Kansas' ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional, but temporarily stayed enforcement of his ruling against state officials for one week.<ref name=kansas/>
:Kansas officials appealed the ruling to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit, while also filing for a permanent stay to last for the duration of the appeal.  On November 7, the Tenth Circuit declined to grant that stay.<ref>{{cite web|title=Order, ''Marie v. Moser''|url=http://hrc-assets.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com//files/assets/resources/MarieTenthDenied.pdf|publisher=Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit|accessdate=November 7, 2014}}</ref> The state defendants then petitioned the U.S. Supreme Court (through Justice Sonia Sotomayor, as Circuit Justice for the Tenth Circuit) to issue a stay pending appeal. On November 10, Sotomayor granted a temporary stay pending consideration of the request while referring the matter to the full court.<ref name="SCOTUSblog">{{cite news|last1=Denniston|first1=Lyle|title=New test of Court’s view on same-sex marriage|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2014/11/new-test-of-courts-view-on-same-sex-marriage/|accessdate=November 10, 2014|work=SCOTUSblog|date=November 10, 2014}}</ref> On November 12, with Justices [[Antonin Scalia]] and [[Clarence Thomas]] dissenting, the Supreme Court declined to issue a stay and lifted the temporary stay. This allowed the injunction in ''Marie'' to take effect, directly preventing Kansas from enforcing its same-sex marriage ban in the two counties subject to the litigation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Snow|first1=Justin|title=Supreme Court allows Kansas same-sex marriages to proceed|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/11/supreme-court-allows-kansas-same-sex-marriages-to-proceed/|accessdate=November 12, 2014|work=Metro Weekly|date=November 12, 2014}}</ref>

====Eleventh Circuit====
;''[[Brenner v. Armstrong]]'' (Florida) 
:Two same-sex marriage cases, ''Brenner v. Scott'' and ''Grimsley v. Scott'', were consolidated on April 21, 2014. On August 21, 2014, U.S. District Judge [[Robert Lewis Hinkle]] found that the state's constitutional and statutory bans on same-sex marriage violate the [[Due Process Clause|Due Process]] and [[Equal Protection Clause]]s. He stayed enforcement of a preliminary injunction that would have prevented Florida from enforcing its bans.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sweeney |first1=Dan|title=Same-sex marriage ban struck down in Florida federal court|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/fl-gay-marriage-federal-court,0,191085.story |accessdate=August 21, 2014|work=Sun-Sentinel|date=August 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Snow|first1=Justin |title=Federal judge rules Florida same-sex marriage ban unconstitutional |url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/08/federal-judge-rules-florida-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional/|accessdate=August 21, 2014|work=Metro Weekly|date=August 21, 2014}}</ref> The state defendants have appealed the case, now ''Brenner v. Armstrong'', to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit|Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ley |first1=John (Clerk of Court)|title=Memorandum to Counsel or Parties (Setting Briefing Due Date), ''Brenner v. Armstrong'', No. 14-14061|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/240579689/14-14061-6-Briefing-Notice|publisher=[[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]]|date=September 19, 2014}}</ref> On October 7, the plaintiffs in both district court cases asked the district court to lift its stay, following the U.S. Supreme Court's action the previous day that allowed several decisions invalidating state bans on same-sex marriage to take effect.<ref>{{cite web|title=Motion to Lift Stay, October 7, 2014|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/242217858/4-14-cv-00107-87 |website=Scribd.com|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/242222698/4-14-cv-00107-88 |title=''Brenner v. Scott'': Plaintiff's Motion to Dissolve Stay |date=October 7, 2014 |publisher=United States District Court for the Northern District of Florida |quote=However, it should be noted that counsel for the Defendants has informed the ''Grimsley'' Plaintiffs that the Defendants oppose the ''Grimsley'' Plaintiffs' similar motion seeking to lift the stay as well.}}</ref> Judge Hinkle rejected that request on November 5,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Anderson|first1=Curt|title=US judge won't lift stay in Florida gay marriage|url=http://www.chron.com/news/article/US-judge-won-t-lift-stay-in-Florida-gay-marriage-5873850.php |accessdate=November 5, 2014|work=Houston Chronicle|agency=Associated Press|date=November 5, 2014}}</ref> and on November 19 the state asked the Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals to extend Hinkle's stay pending appeal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Motion to Extend Stay|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/247127682/14-14066-Motion-to-Extend-Stay|website=Scribd.com|publisher=Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref>

