;'''Missouri'''
:''[[LGBT rights in Missouri|Lawson v. Kelly]]''
:''Lawson'' was filed by the ACLU in state circuit court on June 24, 2014, on behalf of two same-sex couples who had been denied marriage licenses.<ref name="Dahlgren-Petition">{{cite news|last1=Rothert|first1=Anthony (Attorney for Plaintiffs) |title=Petition for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief, ''Lawson and Dahlgren v. Kelly'', No. 1416-CV15024 |url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/231769492/1416-CV15024-Petition|publisher=Sixteenth Judicial Circuit Court of Missouri at Kansas City|date=June 24, 2014}}</ref> Attorney General [[Chris Koster]] intervened and had the case moved to federal court.<ref>{{cite news|date=August 7, 2014|accessdate=September 13, 2014|work=LGBTQ Nation|title=Missouri same-sex marriage case moved to federal court| agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2014/08/missouri-same-sex-marriage-case-moved-to-federal-court/}}</ref> On November 7, 2014, District Judge [[Ortrie Smith]] ruled for the plaintiffs and declared Missouri's ban unconstitutional, but stayed the ruling pending final judgement. The state has announced that it plans to appeal.<ref>{{cite news|work=BuzzFeed News|first=Chris|last=Geidner|date=November 7, 2014|accessdate=November 7, 2014 |url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/missouris-same-sex-marriage-ban-is-unconstitutional-federal| title=Missouri’s Same-Sex Marriage Ban Is Unconstitutional, Federal Judge Rules}}</ref> On November 21, the plaintiffs asked Judge Smith to lift his stay in light of ''[[State of Missouri v. Florida]]'', noting that the state has no position on the request.<ref>{{cite web|title=Motion to Lift Stay |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/247786857/4-14-cv-00622-57|website=Scribd.com |accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref>
