;'''South Carolina'''
:''[[Bradacs v. Haley]]''
:On April 22, 2014, proceedings in this case that seeks to require South Carolina to recognize same-sex marriages from other jurisdictions were stayed until the resolution of ''[[Same-sex marriage in Virginia#Bostic v. Schaefer|Bostic v. Shaefer]]''. The plaintiffs filed a motion for summary judgment on October 20.<ref>{{cite web|title=Plaintiffs' Motion for Summary Judgment|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/243721635/3-13-cv-02351-75 |website=Scribd.com|publisher=U.S. District Court for South Carolina|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref> On November 10, the court removed Governor Nikki Haley as a defendant.<ref>{{cite web|title=Order and Opinion|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/246175378/3-13-cv-02351-89|publisher=U.S. Disctrict Court for South Carolina|accessdate=November 10, 2014}}</ref> On November 18, U.S. District Court Judge [[J. Michelle Childs]] struck down the state's same-sex marriage ban on Fourteenth Amendment grounds and issued a permanent injunction against enforcement of the ban.<ref>{{cite web|title=Order and Opinion |url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/247035992/3-13-cv-02351-97-South-Carolina-Decision|website=Scribd.com|accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref>  
;'''South Dakota'''
:[[LGBT rights in South Dakota|''Rosenbrahn v. Daugaard'']]
:Five plaintiff couples, who filed suit on May 22, 2014, have valid out-of state marriages, and a sixth was denied a license in South Dakota.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Waker |first1= Carson|last2=Burbach |first2= Kevin|title=Six South Dakota couples challenge state's same-sex marriage ban|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2014/05/south-dakota-couples-challenge-states-same-sex-marriage-ban/|accessdate=May 23, 2014|newspaper=LGBTQNation.com|date=May 22, 2014}}</ref> U.S. District Court Judge [[Karen Schreier]] heard arguments on preliminary motions on October 17. The state defendants argued she was bound by the Eighth Circuit's decision in ''[[Citizens for Equal Protection v. Bruning]]'' (2006), which the plaintiffs said did not address the questions they are raising in this case.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Young|first1=Steve|title=No quick decision made in S.D. gay marriage lawsuit |url=http://www.argusleader.com/story/news/politics/2014/10/17/judge-will-file-decision-later-sd-gay-marriage-lawsuit/17432995/ |accessdate=October 21, 2014 |work=Argus Leader|date=October 17, 2014}}</ref> On November 12, Judge Schreier denied the defense's motion to dismiss. She found ''Baker'' is no longer valid precedent and that ''Bruning'' did not address due process or the question of a fundamental right to marry. She dismissed the plaintiffs claim that South Dakota violates their right to travel. She set a briefing schedule to conclude December 8.<ref>{{cite web|title=Order on Motion to Dismiss|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/246625606/4-14-cv-04081-38-Order|website=Scribd.com|publisher=U.S. District Court for South Dakota|accessdate=November 14, 2014}}</ref>

===State courts===
Note: In the United States, the name of the court where a civil complaint or a petition is initially filed, and the trial is held, varies by state. The term used may be county court, circuit court, district court, or superior court.

'''Arkansas:''' ''[[Wright v. Arkansas]]''
:A circuit court judge issued a ruling on May 9, 2014, striking down the state constitution's same-sex marriage ban.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carpenter|first1=Dale|title=Arkansas state court strikes down ban on same-sex marriages |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/volokh-conspiracy/wp/2014/05/09/arkansas-state-court-strikes-down-ban-on-same-sex-marriages/|accessdate=October 11, 2014|work=Washington Post|date=May 9, 2014}}</ref> On May 15, 2014, the judge clarified his order, striking down the statutory ban as well. The next day the [[Arkansas Supreme Court]] stayed enforcement of his ruling pending appeal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Conlon|first1=Kevin|title=Court halts Arkansas same-sex marriages |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/05/16/justice/same-sex-marriage/|accessdate=October 11, 2014|work=CNN Justice |date=May 16, 2014}}</ref> On October 7, the plaintiffs filed a petition for summary judgment citing actions by the U.S. Supreme Court the day before and asking for expedited consideration,<ref>{{cite news|last1=DeMillo|first1=Andrew|title=Couples ask Arkansas court to strike marriage ban|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/oct/7/couples-ask-arkansas-court-to-strike-marriage-ban/|accessdate=11 October 2014|work=Washington Times|agency=Associated Press|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> which the court granted.<ref>{{cite news|title=AR Supreme Court to Hear Arguments in Same Sex Marriage Case|url=http://www.arkansasmatters.com/story/d/story/ar-supreme-court-to-hear-arguments-in-same-sex-mar/38142/V1FDNhoYEUuA5s1cl5VLMw|accessdate=October 23, 2014|work=Arkansas Matters|date=October 23, 2014}}</ref> The court heard oral arguments on November 20.<ref>{{cite news|last1=DeMillo|first1=Andrew|title=Arkansas Supreme Court takes up gay marriage case|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/nov/20/2-courts-set-to-take-up-gay-marriage-in-arkansas/|accessdate=November 20, 2014|work=Washington Times|agency=Associated Press|date=November 20, 2014}}</ref>

'''Florida''': ''[[Pareto v. Ruvin]]'' and ''[[Same-sex marriage in Florida#Huntsman v. Heavilin|Huntsman v. Heavilin]]''
:''Pareto v. Ruvin'' and ''Huntsman v. Heavilin'' are two state circuit court (i.e. trial-level) cases where Florida's ban on same-sex marriage has been found unconstitutional. Both decisions have been stayed and both are under appeal to the state [[Florida Third District Court of Appeal|Third District Court of Appeal]]; all parties have asked this court to pass the consolidated cases directly to the [[Florida Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news|work=Miami Herald| date=October 13, 2014| date=October 13, 2014| title= Bondi: Let Florida Supreme Court decide same-sex marriage now |url= http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/gay-south-florida/article2709200.html| first=Steve |last=Rothaus }}</ref>

'''Kansas:''' ''[[LGBT rights in Kansas#State Court Cases|Nelson v. Kan. Dep't of Revenue]]''
:Same-sex marriage recognition case filed in [[Kansas District Courts|state district court]], where the plaintiffs are seeking recognition of their out-of-state marriage licenses for the purpose of filing a joint state income tax return.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rothschild|first=Scott|title=Same-sex married couples file lawsuit against state over tax treatment|url=http://www2.ljworld.com/news/2013/dec/31/same-sex-married-couples-file-lawsuit-against-stat/|accessdate=October 14, 2014|publisher=Lawrence Journal-World|date=December 31, 2013}}</ref><ref name="KSPet">{{cite news|last=Brown|first=David (Atty. for the Plaintiffs)|title=Petition (Initial), ''Nelson v. Kan. Dep't of Revenue'', No. 13 C 1465|url=http://worldonline.media.clients.ellingtoncms.com/news/documents/2013/12/31/2013_12_30_Petition.pdf|accessdate=May 22, 2014|publisher=[[Kansas District Courts]], Shawnee Co., Div. 7|date=December 30, 2013}}</ref>

'''Louisiana:''' ''[[LGBT rights in Louisiana#State lawsuit|In Re Costanza and Brewer]]''
:A lesbian couple who married in California sought to have their marriage recognized for the purpose of adoption. On February 5, 2014, Judge Edward Rubin ruled in for the plaintiffs in ''In Re Costanza and Brewer'' and authorized the adoption in a separate action,<ref>{{cite news|last=Goff|first=Jessica|title=Same-sex couple clear adoption hurdle |url=http://www.theadvertiser.com/story/news/local/2014/02/13/same-sex-couple-clear-adoption-hurdle/5473533/|accessdate=April 19, 2014|newspaper=The Advertiser|date=February 13, 2014}}</ref> without ruling on their challenge to Louisiana's ban on same-sex marriage. On September 22, Rubin found Louisiana's ban an unconstitutional violation of the [[equal protection clause|equal protection]], the [[due process clause|due process]], and the [[full faith and credit clause]]s of the U.S. Constitution.<ref name=buzzfeed20140922/> He ordered the state to allow the plaintiffs to file a joint state income tax return and to allow their adoption to proceed. He enjoined the state from enforcing laws that "prohibit a person from marrying a person of the same sex".<ref>[http://sblog.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Louisiana-marriage-state-court-ruling.pdf Order, ''Costanza v. Caldwell'', March 22, 2014], accessed March 24, 2014</ref> State officials announced plans to appeal directly to the [[Louisiana Supreme Court]]<ref name=buzzfeed20140922/> and he stayed enforcement of his ruling.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caswell|first1=Micah|title=Fast Facts Regarding In Re: Costanza and Brewer: Freedom to Marry in Louisiana|url=http://equalityla.org/fast-facts-regarding-re-costanza-brewer-freedom-marry-louisiana/|publisher=Equality Louisiana|accessdate=September 25, 2014|ref=September 24, 2014}}</ref>

'''Mississippi:''' ''[[LGBT rights in Mississippi#Divorce of same-sex couples|Czekala-Chatham v. Melancon]]''
:Same-sex divorce case; dismissed for lack of jurisdiction on December 2, 2013 (Chancery Ct. Dist. 3). Appeal filed three weeks later in [[Mississippi Court of Appeals|state appellate court]]; briefing concluded November 29, 2014.

'''Missouri:''' ''[[LGBT rights in Missouri#Lawsuits|State of Missouri v. Florida]]'' 
:In June 2014, St. Louis officials licensed four same-sex marriages in order to provide the basis for a lawsuit when the state ordered them to stop the practice.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pistor|first1=Nicholas |title=Battle over same-sex marriages in St. Louis headed to court|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/battle-over-same-sex-marriages-in-st-louis-headed-to/article_7fe77475-63f4-5d44-8c25-87aa4449946f.html|accessdate=September 25, 2014|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=June 26, 2014}}</ref> St. Louis Circuit Judge Rex Burlison held a hearing in the suit on September 29 in state circuit court.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Salter|first1=Jim|title=St. Louis Challenge to Gay Marriage Ban in Court |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/sep/29/st-louis-challenge-to-gay-marriage-ban-in-court/ |accessdate=November 5, 2014|work=Washington Times|agency=Associated Press|date=September 29, 2014}}</ref> He ruled for the plaintiffs on November 5, finding that Missouri's refusal to license same-sex marriages violates the Missouri and federal constitutions.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moore|first1=Doug|title=Judge rules that gay marriage ban in Missouri is unconstitutional |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/judge-rules-that-gay-marriage-ban-in-missouri-is-unconstitutional/article_f9e3bd74-d9bf-5337-ba22-88cd5614e59d.html |accessdate=November 5, 2014|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=November 5, 2014}}</ref>

'''Texas:''' ''[[In re Marriage of J.B. and H.B.]]''
:A state district court granted a same-sex couple the divorce they filed for in 2009 and ruled the state's same-sex marriage ban unconstitutional as applied to this case. The [[Texas Courts of Appeals]] ruled that district courts do not have jurisdiction in such matters and reversed the decision. The [[Texas Supreme Court]] heard oral arguments on November 5, 2013.

'''Texas:''' ''[[Same-sex marriage in Texas#In the Matter of the Marriage of A.L.F.L. and K.L.L.|In the Matter of the Marriage of A.L.F.L. and K.L.L.]]''
:On February 18, 2014, a same-sex couple, married in Washington D.C., filed a lawsuit for divorce and child custody.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lawsuits Pending|url=http://www.marriageequality.org/lawsuits |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> On April 23, 2014, a state district court judge found Section 32 of the Texas Constitution and three portions of the Texas Family Code unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news|title=Judge: Texas can't bar gay marriage — or divorce |url=http://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/Judge-Texas-can-t-bar-gay-marriage-or-divorce-5425778.php?t=ac46f8d19dabfb0f9d |accessdate=May 16, 2014|date=April 23, 2014|first=Michael|last=Casady}}</ref> On April 25, 2014, Texas Attorney General [[Greg Abbott]] intervened to appeal the decision, and on May 28, 2014, the appellate court directed the district court to vacate its order because the state had not been notified that the plaintiffs were challenging the state constitution and statutes.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}

